<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Injured S. African Soccer Players Released from Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Six players of local premier league club Moroka Swallows were
injured Sunday afternoon at George Goch stadium in Johannesburg
when lightning struck the pitch.
</P>
<P>
The game was first suspended and then cancelled, the first
time in the country that a soccer match was cancelled due to
lightning strike.
</P>
<P>
Two players were taken to hospital after they were knocked
unconscious and the other four suffered no serious injury.
</P>
<P>
Premier Soccer League (PSL) spokesman Andrew Dipela said the
PSL would on Tuesday make an announcement on whether or not it
would be replayed.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened in the last 12 minutes of the game when
Jomo Cosmos led 2-0.
</P>
<P>
Swallows spokesman Godfrey Gxowa said it was a traumatic
experience for the players, but he did not expect the incident to
have any psychological affect on them.
</P>
<P>
"Swallows lost a player on the pitch about 15 years ago and
while it did have an affect on the club, the players did overcome
the psychological pain over time," Gxowa said.
</P>
<P>
"To see so many players struck by lightning was a frightening
experience and really an eye-opener for everybody that such
incidents can, and do, happen."
</P>
<P>
He said he was pleased with Cosmos' coach Jomo Sono's reaction
on Monday when Sono said in an interview he was more concerned on
the players' safety than winning the game.
</P>
<P>
An official at the Johannesburg metro emergency management
services, Charles Terre Blanche, said Monday that except for the
six soccer players who were injured, there were four other
incidents in Johannesburg on Sunday where people were injured by
lightning.
</P>
<P>
None of the incidents were because of a direct hit by
lightning, but by the lightning hitting the ground, he said,
adding that it could be fatal as it causes high-voltage surges.
</P>
<P>
"This is what happened to the soccer players. They received an
electrical shock from the ground," Terre Blanche said.
</P>
<P>
He said electrical storms were normal in South Africa for this
time of year, when everything was still dry.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, a Johannesburg high school pupil, who was
thought to be a cricket star on the rise, was struck dead by
lightning after a cricket match.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
