<HEADLINE> New Panda Breeding At Beijing Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The progress in giant panda
breeding research at the Beijing Zoo has helped twin panda cubs
survive their most vulnerable period.
</P>
<P>
The twin pandas in question are already a month old and are
doing normal. The survival rate of cubs in artificial surroundings
is quite low, says Zhang Jinguo, the zoo's senior
veterinarian. The major reason is in the artificial propagation. A
mother panda generally looks after only one of the twins and
the other needs assistance.
</P>
<P>
After many trials, researchers at the zoo decided to use two
special breeding methods: one involved alternating natural care
with artificial care, the other involves producing milk that
provided immunity similar to that provided by the mother.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is on the verge of extinction. Statistics show
a decrease to between 900 and 1,200 in an area that is limited to
mountainous parts of China's Sichuan, Shaanxi, and Gansu provinces.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Zoo, which is China's largest, has had some success
in establishing a self-sufficient giant panda group with one wild
and 15 zoo-bred pandas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
