<HEADLINE> Low Turnout, Close Races Expected in November Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Republican and Democratic
leaders agree that the upcoming midterm elections in the United
States will be marked by low turnout and close races.
</P>
<P>
Democrats said that in an off-year election where the party
that controls the White House usually loses, their hope is to
break even in House of Representatives and Senate races.
Republicans said they will pick up seats, but there will be no
repetition of the 1994 Republican landslide.
</P>
<P>
Representative Martin Frost, a Democrat and chairman of the
House Democratic campaign committee, predicted "a very close
election. Most of the national polls show this in a dead heat. We
think there will be a lot of races that will be decided by 1,000
and 2,000 votes."
</P>
<P>
"These are local races," said Representative John Linder, a
Republican and chairman of the House Republican Campaign Committee
"For some time, I've been saying we'd gain 10 to 15 seats based on
local political fundamentals. And I never did believe it was a
referendum on Bill Clinton," he said on CBS' "Face the Nation."
</P>
<P>
Democrats insisted that would be a plus as their candidates
press themes of Republican shortcomings in such areas as
education, health care and campaign finance."
</P>
<P>
In the last non-presidential-year election, 1994, Republicans
gained 54 seats in the House and nine in the Senate to win control
of both chambers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
