<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's GDP Growth Tops 6.4 PC Yearly Since </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has achieved
averaged 6.4 percent growth rate in real gross domestic product
(GDP) per year since 1992/93, Minister of Economic Development
and Cooperation Girma Birru said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting on rural roads and transport here, Girma
said strong recovery has been witnessed in performance of the
Ethiopian economy since the launching of the economic reform
program where growth in real GDP averaged 6.4 percent per annum
between 1992/93 and 1997/98, up from a less than 2 percent
average growth in the 1980's.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the agricultural, industrial and services
sectors have also been growing by 4.3, 9.5 and 8.5 percent per
annum respectively during the stated period.
</P>
<P>
Inflation has been contained at less than 5 percent during the
past five years, Girma noted.
</P>
<P>
"Such growth performance was accompanied by a marked increase
in domestic saving and investment which rose to 7 and 20 percent
of GDP respectively in 1997/98 from 3.5 and 10.5 percent share in
1990/91," he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The minister told participants that the nation has adopted a
long-term development strategy referred to as "agricultural
development led industrialization" aimed at revitalizing the
agricultural sector and hence laying a sound basis for industrial
growth.
</P>
<P>
However, he said despite such positive achievements, Ethiopia
is still challenged by low level of education and health
standards and that the economic infrastructure need to go a long
way to compare even with African standards.
</P>
<P>
In a similar development, Ethiopian Vice-Minister of Trade and
Industry Biruk Debebe disclosed here Friday that the nation is
expected to achieve a 7-8 percent economic growth in current
1998/99. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
