<HEADLINE> Over 5,700 Iraqi Children Die in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 26 (Xinhua) -- A total of 5,767 Iraqi children
under five and 2,623 adults died in September of malnutrition and
various curable diseases, a report released by the Health Ministry
Monday showed.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the high death toll to the eight-year-old
U.N. sanctions against Iraq, which have left Iraq in severe
shortage of medicine and many Iraqis under starvation.
</P>
<P>
The number of children that under five and adults died of
malnutrition and curable diseases in September, 1989 was 286 and
439 respectively before the sanctions, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed on Iraq shortly after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990 and will not be lifted until the U.N. weapons
inspectors certify that Baghdad has eliminated all weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The report also showed that mortality of children under five
reached 52,052 in the first nine months in 1998 while that of
adults, aged over 50, were 52,174.
</P>
<P>
And a total of 410,794 children below five and 621,958 adults
above 50 had died since the beginning of the sanctions till
September of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
