<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni, U.S. Envoy Discuss Congo (K) Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni and U.S. Special Envoy to the Great Lakes Region Howard
Wolpe discussed the situation in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) here Monday.
</P>
<P>
They reviewed the proposals which have so far been made by the
region on how to resolve the conflict in the DRC, a press release
from the President's Office said Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
It said the special envoy was particularly interested in the
mechanism for the implementation of a cease-fire and subsequent
negotiations with a view to seeing how his government can be of
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Monday's East African weekly reported that the U.S. government
has asked Uganda and Rwanda to withdraw their troops from the
12-week-long conflict.
</P>
<P>
The paper said this move by Washington was based on fears that
the rising number of African countries intervening in the Congo
(K) civil war could worsen the conflict.
</P>
<P>
However, while addressing a press conference on October 21,
Museveni refuted press reports that the U.S. government had
ordered Uganda to get out of Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
"I talked to them (Americans) about the press reports and they
denied such claims," the president told dozens of reporters
emphatically.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the rebellion against Congolese
President Laurent Kabila in early August, Uganda and Rwanda have
been accused of being behind the Tutsi rebels, a charge both
governments denied vehemently.
</P>
<P>
Kenya and Tanzania joined Uganda in the view that all foreign
troops should pull out of Congo (K) when presidents of these
countries met in Nairobi on October 18.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe decided to send
2,000 more troops to eastern Congo to reinforce the 3,000-strong
Zimbabwean troops there, an indication that the crisis there is
still worsening fast.
</P>
<P>
With the widening of the crisis, there are growing concerns
that more and more African countries will be drawn into the
conflict, making the regional crisis a continental one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
