<HEADLINE> UNITA Organizational Secretary Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Franco Marcolino Nhani,
Secretary for Organizational Affairs in Angola's biggest
opposition movement of UNITA, declared to resign here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued at a press conference, Nhani said he
made the decision because the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) has continued its war policy,
which he said runs against the will of Angolan people.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA official who is also a UNITA representative at the
joint committee for national peace process, said he held that
implementation of the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol, which has
opened up the peace process in Angola, is the only way to free
the country of its three-decade-long civil war.
</P>
<P>
The fresh crisis of the peace process, he said, has put the
Angolan people on the brink of renewing the civil war, which runs
counter to the interest of the country and the will of the
people. For this he decided to resign from his post in UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Nhani did not say whether he would join the break-away UNITA
Renovation Committee, but he made it clear that he would stick to
his ideal of peace, national unity and reconciliation, and keep
loyal to the Angolan people who have voted him into Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Nhani who joined UNITA in 1974, was elected organizational
secretary of the party in 1995 at the eighth national congress
and was sent to Luanda as a representative of the joint committee
of the peace process in Angola in the same year.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, he was chosen as a UNITA parliament member to the
Angolan National Assembly. On April 1, 1998, he was appointed as
one of the leaders of the UNITA delegation in Luanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
