<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relief Food Distributed at Southwest Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food Program
(WFP) has begun distributing relief food supplies to more than
25,000 rural families facing food shortages in southwestern
Rwanda, said a WFP report available here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Over the next three weeks, the WFP will distribute some 1,200
tons of food aid in Gikongoro Prefecture, where many families are
living in such poor terrain they can no longer grow enough food
to sustain their families.
</P>
<P>
"Most of these families have only a 50 square-foot plot of
land to cultivate," said Gerard van Dijk, WFP representative in
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"They're trying to grow their meager crops on steep, hillside
areas where the quality of soil has eroded over the years. This
makes it virtually impossible for them to harvest enough food to
carry them through to the next season," he said.
</P>
<P>
WFP will distribute a combination of maize and beans in all of
Gikongoro's 13 communes, providing assistance to more than 20
percent of the prefecture's 500,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
The distribution has been timed to coincide with the start of
the planting season. Families are now cultivating for the next
harvest due in December. Most residents are hoping that this
season will be better than the last harvest in May which brought
in poor yields.
</P>
<P>
Because the land area most families in Gikongoro have to
cultivate is so small, they can only expect to grow enough food
to feed their immediate need and to put a small amount of their
crops aside as seedlings for the next season, said the WFP
report.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, any reduction in their crops will threaten their
ability to survive, the report added.
</P>
<P>
"Because the last harvest was poor, many families consumed the
little food they reaped and now have virtually nothing to eat or
plant," said Van Dijk.
</P>
<P>
"We're working with other agencies right now to ensure that
really needy families get both seeds as well as relief food to
sustain them throughout the planting season," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This distribution will not only prevent families from going
hungry now, but it will carry them through the next few months,"
said Van Dijk.
</P>
<P>
WFP is currently feeding over 520,000 people in Rwanda, more
than 360,000 of whom are internally displaced people in the
volatile northwest region of the tiny central African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
