<HEADLINE> Israeli Central Bank to Increase Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Israeli central bank
announced on Monday that it will increase the interest rates for
the first time this year in a bid to check the devaluation of the
shekel.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Israel Governor Jacob Frenkel said in Jerusalem that
the key lending rate will rise by 2 percentage points to 11.5
percent as of November 1.
</P>
<P>
Frenkel said that it was necessary to take such a step in
order to stabilize the foreign currency markets.
</P>
<P>
As the foreign investors rushed to sell off the shekel in light
of current global economic crisis, the shekel has depreciated
sharply against the U.S. dollar this month.
</P>
<P>
At the end of September, the representative rate was only 3.90
shekels against one dollar. But the reate hit a record of 4.367
shekels against the dollar last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After the central bank's announcement, the shekel appreciated
on Monday and the new representative rate rose to 4.18 shekels
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Frenkel said that the increase of interest rates would also
prevent the growth of living cost and the high inflation rate of 7
percent in 1997. The government is trying to reduce it to 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Israeli industrial leaders have called on
the central bank to refrain from raising the interest rates,
fearing such a move would bring about an economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Since January the Israeli central bank has cut the key lending
rate by 3.9 percent in a bid to spur the economic growth. And
currently the key lending rate is 9.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
