<HEADLINE> Iran to Hold Nationwide City Council Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced on Monday that
the first nationwide elections for city councils would be held on
February 26, 1999.
</P>
<P>
An Interior Ministry statement requires applicants to sign up
for the elections by January 3, 1999, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that applicants should be above 25 and
capable of reading and writing, with at least one-year's record of
stay in the constituency.
</P>
<P>
Those applying for membership in the city councils should
resign from government posts by November 4, 1998, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian constitution has accredited the city councils,
which are separate from the municipalities, with the
administration of the affairs of the cities.
</P>
<P>
Governors and other civil officials appointed by the
government should observe the decisions made by the councils, the
constitution said.
</P>
<P>
Although the constitution underlined the need to form city
councils, but so far no such councils existed in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the elections would be another arena for
the conservatives and the moderates after Friday's election for
the third Experts Assembly which has the right to determine and
dismiss the supreme leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
