<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Promote Rural Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Roads
Authority Monday stressed the need to create conditions for
promoting rural transport infrastructure and transport means to
minimize the existing transport problem in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting on the rural roads and transport strategy
development here, Tesfamichael Nahusenay, General Manager of the
authority, said despite the 110 percent increase of road network
since 1988, Ethiopia has one of the lowest road densities
compared to average Africa standard.
</P>
<P>
Tesfamichael said Ethiopia's modern transport system covers
about 20 percent of the existing transport demand, adding that
the remaining 80 percent of the population and goods movement
depends on traditional means of transport, primarily walking,
head and back loading, and animal transport.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the road transport accounts for about 97 percent
of the passenger and freight movement.
</P>
<P>
Opening the three-day meeting, Minister of Economic
Development and Cooperation Girma Birru said the inadequate road
network in Ethiopia has not only resulted in high transport
costs, but also contributed to the problem of inaccessibility to
areas of agriculture potential and social services.
</P>
<P>
The meeting aims to achieve consensus on ways of improving the
rural roads and transport sub-sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
