<HEADLINE> Lebanon Criticizes Palestinian-Israeli Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Fares
Boueiz Monday criticized the Palestinian-Israeli peace deal
signed in Washington, saying Lebanon will never have such an
agreement with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"The deal brings about a great disappointment for the
Palestinian people in their struggle to restore legal rights and
build an independent country," Boueiz said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
This is not a victory for the Palestinians in particular and the
Arabs in general as the settlement was reached after the
Palestinians agreed to the Israeli conditions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We long for a full and real peace which is based on the
implementation of international resolutions and an Israeli serious
withdrawal from its occupied Lebanese and Syrian territories," he
said.
</P>
<P>
After nine days of negotiations at the Wye Plantation near
Washington, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu signed an agreement last Friday,
breaking a 19-month deadlock in the peace talks between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Israel will withdraw its troops from a
further 13.1 percent of the West Bank in three months, while
Palestinians will revoke anti-Israel clauses in their national
charter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he renewed the call on Israel to restart talks with
Lebanon and Syria from where they were broken off. The talks have
been stalled since early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in parts of southern
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
It is also occupying Syrian Golan Heights that it captured in
the 1967 Middle East War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
