<HEADLINE> China to Hold Internet Export Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 27 (Xinhua) -- China is planning to
introduce Internet into China Export Commodity Fair, which is one
of the most influential foreign trade event in the country.
</P>
<P>
Face-to-face talks and Internet trading will become a new trend
for the fair to be held biannually in Guangzhou, officials
attending the current 84th event told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for such a fair are being made by China
International Electronic Commerce Center under the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, the officials
disclosed. The Internet will play the role of introducing
participating enterprises and products, statistics and background
information of previous fairs.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Daming, deputy director of the Center, the
projected Internet event is expected to expand the scale and
influence of the fair, and facilitate the exchange between
exporters and importers.
</P>
<P>
The novelty will also become an extension of the biannual
event, providing chances for further contacts after the
on-the-spot event is closed, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Internet was used for the first time two years ago during the
80th fair when a web-site of the fair was opened. Statistics show
about 4,000 people visit the site everyday.
</P>
<P>
The 83rd fair employed Internet to send invitations to over
2,000 chain stores and department stores.
</P>
<P>
During the current fair, Legend Group, a leading Chinese
computer maker, struck a deal worth 18 million US dollars with a
Hong Kong company.
</P>
<P>
"All these have paved the way for the coming of the Internet
fair in the future," Zhang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
