<HEADLINE> Construction Projects in China Provide Chances to Regional Industry: Chinese Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Investments of some 700
billion U.S. dollars into China's infrastructure projects over the
next two to three years will make China remain a huge market for
international construction industry and flooring sector in
particular, a leading Chinese interior architect said here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the third annual Asia
Pacific flooring exhibition Asiaflor '98 at the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center, Zeng Jian, Chairman of the China
Institute of Interior Architects, said large-scale construction
projects are well going on in China. China, which has recently
successfully withstood both the Asian economic crises and the
disastrous flooding, is maintaining a rapid pace in the
development of national economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zeng's opinions were echoed by Ivan Dai, Chairman of the
Interior Design Association of Hong Kong, who also officiated the
opening ceremony. "The products on display here will provide an
important opportunity for building professionals throughout Asia
to familiarize themselves with the latest trends in flooring."
Such opportunities will make Asiaflor '98 "an informative and
rewarding experience for anyone involved in interior design,
architecture and construction and trade," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mike Chappel, the organizer of Asiaflor '98, said the
exhibition helps to make "contacts between international flooring
suppliers and manufacturers and expanding Asian market."
</P>
<P>
The three-day event has attracted representatives from more
than 180 exhibitors from 30 countries and regions the world over.
Displaying at the exhibition are rugs, carpets, tiles, wood,
laminate, vinyl and rubber flooring as well as fibers, raw
materials, equipment and accessories, installation systems and
underlays.
</P>
<P>
Also arranged for the event were more than a dozen seminar
programs designed to introduce the latest flooring systems,
materials and installation equipment. 
</P>
