<HEADLINE> Thailand Cracks Down on Illegal Alien Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Police and immigration
officials in the Tak province, northern Thailand, have been
ordered to crack down on about 13,000 alien workers who failed to
apply for work permits.
</P>
<P>
The Thai News Agency on Tuesday quoted Tak Governor Huakhan
Tomonsak as saying that the order followed a report that only
about 3,300 alien workers, out of an estimated 16,100, had
registered with the authorities.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that at least 12,800 alien workers, most of
them from Myanmar, are illegally working in the province,
particularly in the garment industry. Under the order, those
arrested will be repatriated immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry requires enterpreneurs to register their
alien workers with the immigration authorities, or will be fined
if they fail to meet the requirement.
</P>
<P>
To hire an alien worker, each employer will be charged 1,000
baht (27 U.S. dollars) as registration fee, 1,000 baht for a
worker permit, 700 baht (19 dollars) for medical checkup and
another 800 bath (21 dollars) for health insurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
