<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Preparing For Meteor Storm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 27 (Xinhua) -- China will open three
observation stations here to help stargazers get a good look at a
meteor storm in the constellation Leo.
</P>
<P>
The storm is expected to occur between 2:00 and 4:00 am on
November 18 (Beijing Time), and will be the first such storm
visible in the eastern hemisphere for the past century.
</P>
<P>
The northeastern part of China will be the best position to
observe the storm, because it can be seen by the naked eye there.
</P>
<P>
Wang Kemin, deputy director of the Chinese Academy of Sciences'
Beijing Observatory, told a press conference here today that the
observatory has also prepared programs for institutions that
specialize in this and astronomers from the Netherlands, the
United States, France, and the Czech Republic are expected to come
to witness the special event.
</P>
<P>
A meteor storm in the constellation Leo was first recorded by
the Chinese in 902 AD, formed by solid fragments of Tempel
Tuttle. The phenomenon occurred approximately every 32 to 33 years.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that the storm will not harm people on earth but
may affect man-made objects in outer space.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
