<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Buys Dollar in Foreign Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's central bank entered
the foreign market Tuesday to buy U.S. dollars in a bid to shore
up the country's financial status, Deputy Governor Kitti
Patpongpibul said.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the dollar purchase aimed mainly to
prepare for the settlement of some outstanding forward
obligations, and to stabilize the baht which has risen about 11
percent against the dollar over the last two months.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said on October 22 that its outstanding net
forward foreign exchange contracts to buy the local currency had
fallen to 9.1 billion dollars as of October 16, compared to 9.4
billion dollars a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
Kitti added that the current rate of the baht (37.5 against the
dollar) was not excessive. The central bank is keen to ensure some
stability, although it does not want to interfere with broader
market trends.
</P>
<P>
"The bank is supervising the market in order not to let the
baht strengthen excessively. But we have no intention to change
its direction," he said. 
</P>
