<HEADLINE> China Increasing Indoor Air Pollution Monitoring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Specialists from provinces and
municipalities and Hong Kong met at a national symposium on
technology of indoor air pollution control here today to
discuss ways to monitor indoor air pollution and purify the air.
</P>
<P>
They discussed air hygiene in kitchens, nicotine smoke, and
formaldehyde released by synthetic wooden floor boards.
</P>
<P>
Participants said that they believe that although China has
clean air standards for hospitals, food, electronics, and
pharmaceutical industries, it does not have any for air in civilian
buildings.
</P>
<P>
They say that indoor air purification technology also needs to
be studied and that indoor materials, domestic chemical products,
and air conditioners are all potential pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Recent research has shown that indoor air pollution may cause
irritation to throats and noses and could also cause an increase
in the number of white blood cells in old people and
children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
