<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improving Administrative Appeals Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 27 (Xinhua) -- A motion to stop illegal and
inappropriate administrative behavior was submitted to China's top
legislative body for review today.
</P>
<P>
A draft of the Administrative Appeals Law is meant to get
administrative offices to act in accordance with the law and to
protect the rights and interests of citizens and organizations.
</P>
<P>
The fifth meeting of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee will study the 41 articles in 7 chapters that
allow for administrative appeals when citizens or organizations
who believe their rights and interests have been violated by
specific administrative behavior.
</P>
<P>
Administrative offices have to fulfill administrative appeals
duty legally and promptly and under the principle of openness and
convenience. They are required to correct every act of wrongdoing
to guarantee that laws and regulations are implemented correctly.
</P>
<P>
Yang Jingyu, director of the State Council's Legislative
Affairs Office, explained the draft to the NPC Standing Committee
and said that it is significant in perfecting the administrative
appeals system, which improves supervision in administrative
offices, urges administrative offices to carry out their functions
legally and correctly, and guards social and economic order,
rights and interests of citizens and organizations, and social
stability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improving Administrative Appeals Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China adopted a system of administrative appeals in the early
1950s and has passed related laws in the past several decades.
</P>
<P>
The State Council developed administrative appeals regulations
in 1990 to further elaborate and develop the system of
administrative appeals. There were 220,000 administrative appeals
cases in the 1991-1997 period nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the regulations has provided useful
experience and has revealed problems as well, according to Yang
Jingyu. For example, individual citizens and organizations have
found administrative appeals inconvenient because of too many
restrictions. And, some administrative offices are afraid of
becoming defendants or try to avoid troubles and refuse to accept
an appeal, he says.
</P>
<P>
Some administrative offices don't get rid of certain
administrative behavior that should be discouraged or corrected,
he adds.
</P>
<P>
The draft clearly defines basic principles of administrative
appeal, limits of appeals, decisions, and legal responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
