<HEADLINE> France Confirms Deposition of Accusations Against Pinochet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- France Tuesday confirmed the
deposition of accusations by three French families against former
Chilean President Augusto Pinochet, which could lead French
authorities to demand the extradition of the general from Britain.
</P>
<P>
The three families said two of their relatives disappeared and
one was assassinated in Chile during the military rule of Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said if
French judicial authorities decide that it is legally appropriate
to ask for the extradition of Pinochet, France would ask Britain
to apply the 1957 bilateral agreement on extradition.
</P>
<P>
While refusing to comment on the on-going legal proceedings in
London, Gazeau-Secret said any future contacts with Britain on
extraditing Pinochet would be made by the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer of the three families has written to Minister of
Justice Elisabeth Guigou, asking her to prepare "in the shortest
time possible to contact her British counterpart for a procedure
of extradition of General Pinochet."
</P>
<P>
The French magistrature also asked for the extradition of
Pinochet Monday evening in a memorandum written by lawyer Me
Bourdon to the Procurator of the Republic in Paris, Jean-Pierre
Dintilhac.
</P>
<P>
Bourdon presented the memorandum in the name of the families
of Enrique Andres Maria Ropert Contreras, a Frenchman killed by
Chile's military authorities in September 1973; Alphonse Rene
Chanfreau, who was arrested by Chilean political police and never
came out of his detention center; and Etienne Pesle, who was
arrested at his office in Santiago by "a Chilean Air Force team"
and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet was arrested on October 16 in London after undergoing
surgery there. His arrest was requested by the Spanish
authorities who, together with Switzerland, have asked for his
extradition for the assassination of Spanish and Swiss
nationals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
