<HEADLINE> China Cracking Down On Foreign Exchange Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 27 (Xinhua) -- China will crack down on
illegal dealings in foreign exchange and black market activities
to guarantee financial and economic stability.
</P>
<P>
A draft of a law was handed over to the Standing Committee of
the 9th National People's Congress this morning for discussion and
it is expected to be adopted by legislators.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, president of the People's Bank of China (BOC),
says that, with the Asian financial crisis, foreign exchange
infractions have run rampant since the fourth quarter of last year
and constitute a serious threat to the stability and safety of
China's economy if they are not stopped immediately.
</P>
<P>
He said that the State Administration of Foreign Exchange and
other departments have launched investigations nationwide and will
deal harshly with foreign exchange infractions.
</P>
<P>
Dai explained that the new law would consider other illegal
deals in foreign exchange as crimes and will have penalties for
people who abet criminals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
