<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fifth Meeting of Mekong River Commission Council  Opens in Hanoi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The fifth meeting of the Council
of the Mekong River Commission (CMRC) opened here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the two-day meeting are officials from four
countries sharing the Mekong river lower basin, namely Vietnam,
Thailand, Laos and Cambodia, and representatives from the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP), the Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) and other
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Minister of Agriculture and Rural Development Le Huy
Ngo, who is CMRC president for the 1998-99 term, chaired the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting focuses discussions on socio-economic development
cooperation program of the four countries, assessment on impacts
of and policies on environmental protection in the basin, and
proper use and protection of the Mekong river water resources.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda is a concrete plan for the Mekong river
basin.
</P>
<P>
Countries located in the basin of the Mekong river have since
1957 cooperated to study the utility of the river, work out
measures to protect its marine resources, preserve the river's
natural characteristics, and minimize bad affects of the river.
</P>
<P>
The four-nation Mekong river commission, set up in 1995, is an
inter-governmental organization. Each commission member country
will hold alternatively the presidency for a one-year term.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Mekong delta covers 3.9 million hectares of land with
2.4 million hectares being reserved for agricultural production
and aquaculture. This region contributes over 40 percent of the
country's agricultural output.
</P>
<P>
Without fresh water provided by Mekong river in the dry season,
around 2 million hectares of land for intensive farming in the
Mekong delta will be contaminated with saline water, affecting the
agricultural production in the Mekong delta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
