</P>
<P>
-- Yugoslavia began what appeared to be serious troop
withdrawals from many positions in Kosovo, only a day before a
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) deadline and under
threat of air strike. NATO is almost certain to extend the
deadline for ordering air strikes against Yugoslav military and
police forces.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin called off a visit to
Austria, citing poor health, three days after his spokesman
asserted that Yeltsin was healthy and had been wounded by rumor
mongering to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Peru and Ecuador, which fought three territorial wars this
century and almost clashed again three months ago, signed a
landmark peace agreement Monday that resolved their violent border
dispute with an innovative plan that includes creation of two
national "peace parks" near the most contested stretch of their
frontier.
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu fought a rear
guard battle Monday against the growing likelihood of early
elections as an odd alliance of liberals, security hawks and
religious parties aimed to topple his government in the fallout
from the Middle East peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Tests on Iraqi warheads largely back a U.S. assertion that
Baghdad loaded VX nerve gas onto missiles before the Gulf War.
The report to the United Nations Security Council was submitted by
17 scientists who analyzed findings from U.S. Swiss and French
labs.
</P>
<P>
An insurance-redlining jury ordered Nationwide Mutual to pay
100 million dollars in punitive and 500,000 dollars in
compensatory damages after a fair-housing group sued it for bias
against black neighborhoods in Richmond, Virginia. The firm vowed
to appeal to the state's high court. 
</P>
