<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Right-Wingers Urged to Halt Incitement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- A rightist party in Israel's
coalition government joined President Ezer Weizman Tuesday in his
call for a halt of incitement campaign launched by right-wingers
against Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Yitzhak Levy, leader of the National Religious Party (NRP),
was quoted by Israel Radio as calling on religious and political
leaders of the right wings to clearly condemn the incitement
campaign.
</P>
<P>
In recent demonstrations held in the West Bank and outside the
prime minister's residence, some Jewish settlers and right-wing
politicians accused Netanyahu of "betrayal" by signing a
land-for-peace deal with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat last
week. Some called him "a traitor."
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Netanyahu Tuesday morning, Weizman said the
prime minister had achieved a "good agreement" and it would be
"very grave" if there would be a repetition of the incitement
waged against "someone else," referring to slain prime minister
Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
Rabin, who jointly started the peace process with Arafat by
signing the historic Oslo Accords in 1993, was assassinated by an
extreme Jewish rightist in 1995. The rightists had accused him of
"treason."
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid said since the assassination of
Rabin, he has sworn never again to accept calling the prime
minister of Israel as a "traitor" again.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who is also education minister in Netanyahu's cabinet,
said he believes the prime minister can prevent a political
assassination.
</P>
<P>
Security measures have been strengthened to protect Netanyahu,
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon and Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai since they returned from the U.S. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
After nine days of negotiations, Palestinian and Israeli
leaders signed the peace agreement at the White House last Friday,
which broke a 19-month deadlock in the Palestinian-Israeli peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Israel will withdraw its troops from 13.1
percent of the West Bank and free hundreds of Palestinian
prisoners, while the Palestinian side will step up efforts to
crack down on Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
As a fresh sign of the incitement campaign, a poster jointly
made by rightist groups and occupying about one quarter of the
front page of the Israeli daily Haaretz Tuesday said that
Netanyahu and Sharon should be responsible for the "shameful
agreement."
</P>
<P>
"We voted for you and we put you in power," the poster reads,
"we will remember...we won't forget...and we won't forgive..."
</P>
<P>
On top of the poster, which appeared Monday on the front page
of another daily The Jerusalem Post, were the white-and-black
photos of Netanyahu and Sharon.
</P>
<P>
Levy's party, the NRP, which strongly opposed the interim
agreement, dealt a blow to Netanyahu Monday when its members in
the Knesset (Parliament) Law Committee joined the opposition in
voting for a decision to present two bills calling for early
elections to the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
The bills have passed in the preliminary reading in late July
and need to pass three more readings before becoming law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu continued his campaign to win approval for
the agreement. After meeting twice with Likud ministers and
appealing for their support Monday, he met with several ministers
again Tuesday, including Communications Minister Limor Livnat, who
has expressed her opposition to the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
