<HEADLINE> Britain Rules out Talks With Menem Over Falklands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The British government on
Tuesday ruled out possible negotiations over the sovereignty of
the disputed Falkland (Malvinas) Islands with Argentine President
Carlos Menem during his landmark visit to London.
</P>
<P>
Menem, accompanied by senior Argentine cabinet ministers and
some 100 businessmen, is due to arrive here later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said he hoped Menem's
six-day visit would reconcile Britain and Argentina after the
brief but bloody war they fought over the remote South Atlantic
islands in 1982.
</P>
<P>
But he told the BBC that there was no question of negotiations
on the status of the Falklands, which Argentina calls the Malvinas
and has claimed for 165 years.
</P>
<P>
"There is going to be no substantive discussion on the
Falklands. I am quite sure President Menem will repeat the
well-known Argentine position," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will very firmly state Britain's position, which is that
there will be no change in the sovereignty of the Falkland Islands
unless the Falklanders themselves ask for it."
</P>
<P>
Cook, noting that Britain was the number one European Union
investor in Argentina, said "while we remember the past we
shouldn't let it prevent us from building a future together and
this is a very different Argentina."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Argentina's ambassador to Britain Rogelio Pfirter
told the BBC that he hoped Menem's visit, the first by an
Argentine leader since 1960, would open "a new chapter in
bilateral relations."
</P>
<P>
"It will represent a major contribution to reconciliation and
friendship between Britain and Argentina. It will help us to
enhance existing cooperation notably in the area of trade and
investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Britain and Argentina needed to put the war, which claimed
1,000 lives, behind them, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We should recognize that the war existed but we should also
recognize that we look at the future as modern nations and build
the future together if possible." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
