<HEADLINE> Palestinian Police Arrest Suspects in Hebron Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian security forces
announced Tuesday afternoon that they have arrested two
Palestinians suspected of killing a Jewish settler in the divided
West Bank town of Hebron Monday, local television reported.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the two had confessed to the murder and also
the killing of another Israeli man in a communal farm outside
Jerusalem about two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops enforced a curfew in the Israeli-controlled
part of Hebron Tuesday, barring about 30,000 Palestinians from
leaving their homes. Palestinians are even not allowed to go
to work or school.
</P>
<P>
The curfew, imposed Monday night after the slaying of Danny
Vargas, a 29-year-old security guard from the nearby Jewish
settlement of Kiryat Arba, was the third time since August that
the Palestinians in the Israeli-run sector of the city are not
allowed to go out.
</P>
<P>
Vargas was shot three times when driving back home Monday
afternoon and his body was dumped on a Hebron street. Palestinian
doctors rushing to the site after informed by a Palestinian
journalist who saw the body tried in vain to revive him.
</P>
<P>
As hundreds of Jewish settlers were taking part in the funeral
of Vargas in Hebron Tuesday, Palestinians took to the street of
another West Bank town of Nablus to mourn Mohammed Zalmout, a
68-year-old Palestinian also murdered Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The body of Zalmout was found outside the Jewish settlement
of Itamar, south of Nablus, several hours after the shooting
of Vargas. An anonymous phone call said that was an avenge killing.
</P>
<P>
There were fears that the terror attacks, conducted only
several days after Israeli and Palestinian leaders signed a
land-for-peace deal in the United States, would help derail the
peace process again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
