<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Want Fundamental Change in Health System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The majority of Canadian people
believe their health-care system needs fundamental changes or a
complete restructuring, a survey by researchers at the Harvard
University School of Public Health shows.
</P>
<P>
The survey, in which 1,006 Canadians were interviewed by phone,
found that 56 percent believed there are "some good things (in the
health-care system), but fundamental changes are needed." A
further 23 percent said the system needed to be completely rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
When the researchers asked the same question in another survey
10 years ago, only five percent believed the system needed to be
rebuilt and 37 percent thought fundamental changes were needed.
</P>
<P>
"Canadians once (thought they) had the Shangri-la of medical
systems in the industrialized world, but they don't see it that
way any more," said health policy professor Robert Blendon, the
survey's head researcher.
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, 56 percent of Canadians thought the system
worked well and only minor changes were needed, but the number had
dropped to 20 percent in the interviews conducted between April
and June this year, Blendon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0070 </DOCNO>
