<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Party Committees at Grass-roots Support Villagers' Democratic Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 27 (Xinhua) -- An amendment to China's Organic
Law for Villagers' Committee proposes that Party committees at the
grass-roots continue to be the core of local leadership
while supporting villagers in exercising democratic rights.
</P>
<P>
The draft was submitted to the Standing Committee of China's
National People's Congress today. Zhou Keyu, deputy head of the
NPC Law Committee, says that self government was a great invention
for improving rural democracy under the leadership of the Communist
Party of China, and that the amendment finally clarifies the
relation between villagers committees and Party committees in
villages.
</P>
<P>
The relation between villagers' committees and Party committees
in villages is one of the three items causing heated discussions
during the amendment of the Organic Law for Villagers'
Committees. The other two are the relations between villagers'
committees and township governments and the relations between
villagers' committees and economic organizations in villages.
</P>
<P>
Those who favor the township government as the leader of
villagers' committees believe that this will make it easier for
the township government to give instructions to villages. But others
argue that, as the leader of the villagers' committee, the township
government may appoint village heads, resulting in villagers'
committees losing their rights.
</P>
<P>
After repeated discussions, most members of the NPC Standing
Committee have agreed that township governments should be
directors instead of leaders of villagers' committees. While
villagers have the right of self-government, the local villagers'
committee has the responsibility of assisting the government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
