<HEADLINE> Iran Launches New Initiative for Decentralization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government has
launched a new initiative to offer more authority to provincial
governors general in order to prepare the grounds toward
decentralization, the official news agency IRNA reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Vice President and head of the Administrative and Recruiting
Organization Mohammad Baqerian was quoted as saying that under the
new plan, which became effective last week, governors general
would act as the government's high commissioners in dealing with
provincial administrative affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said that the decentralization drive would enhance the
decision-making power of provincial officials and enable them to
offer more services to local inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
Baqerian underlined the need for decentralization of executive
affairs and change in the administration structure of the
country, saying that the issue of rendering more authority to
provincial officials, which was seriously followed in the past
two decades, is given top priority under the administration of
President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Given the rapid pace of population growth, expansion of cities
and sophisticated political, security, cultural and social
issues, the country can no longer be administered on basis of old
patterns, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Observers here see the initiative as a step by Khatami's
government to push forward his proposed political development, or
reform, in the country, which was opposed by the conservatives
who give priorities to solving the country's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Another step was to hold the first nationwide elections to
form city councils, according to an announcement by the Interior
Ministry on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Baqerian also noted that the objective of the new plan is
to consolidate position of the high commissioners, strengthen the
role that governors general play in coordinating and supervising
over local affairs and encourage further participation in social,
political and cultural activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
