<HEADLINE> China Expands Export of High-Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The 84th China Export
Commodity Fair sold new and high-tech products worth over 500
million yuan (60.26 million US dollars) in the first 12 days since
it opened here on October 15, accounting for over 10 percent of
the transactions done so far, fair organizers said.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that China's efforts to readjust its export
structure amid adverse impact of the Asian financial crisis have
already produced results, analysts pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In order to facilitate the export of high technology, the
biannual event for the first time introduced a 400-square-meter
information industry hall, which has been a focus of attention.
</P>
<P>
A staff member of the Guangzhou Zhenhua Light Industry
Enterprise Group said that her booth has received an average of
over 30 clients every day since the fair opened.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shangtong, a salesman of the Shanghai Donghai Computer
Co. Ltd., which is the producer of the first personnel computer in
China, said that his company is very optimistic about the export
prospects since the company mainly targets Africa and the Middle
East while clients from Europe and North America are also showing
interest.
</P>
<P>
The current fair has drawn 33 high-tech companies from across
China who are displaying 140 varieties of products. In comparison,
only two high-tech firms were present during the 80th fair.
</P>
<P>
Legend Group, a leading Chinese computer maker which attended
the 80th fair, struck a deal worth 18 million US dollars at the
first day of the on-going fair.
</P>
<P>
The Haier Group, a leading refrigerator maker, has already
received over 30 million US dollars of orders during the fair.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, products with high technology content accounted
for only 5.3 percent of China's total exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
