<HEADLINE> Israeli Military Authority Warns of Escalation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Following two murders in the
West Bank, the Israeli military authority has warned of an
escalation of violence in the territories, local daily Haaretz
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted the authority as saying that in advance of
the implementation of the second redeployment in the West Bank,
the killing made the atmosphere "extremely tense."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a 29-year-old Jewish settler was shot dead in the
West Bank city of Hebron. Several hours later the body of a
65-year-old Palestinian was found near the West Bank Jewish
settlement of Itamar.
</P>
<P>
After the incidents, Israeli troops imposed a general closure
on Hebron Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a curfew was imposed on the Palestinians who live
in the Israeli-controlled sector of the city. And about 30,000
Palestinians are barred from leaving their homes.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman said the murders were "not a
good start for the accord signed at Wye (in the U.S.)."
</P>
<P>
But he noted that it "shows how necessary such an agreement is
in order to prevent such incidents in the future."
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians signed a land-for-security
agreement at the White House last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Israel will hand over 13 percent of the
West Bank to the Palestinians in the second troop redeployment, in
return for the fulfillment of the Palestinian commitments to
fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But there is a fear that the anti-peace forces from both sides
will make efforts to halt the implementation of the
agreement. 
</P>
