<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder Formally Elected German Chancellor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The German parliament Tuesday
formally elected Gerhard Schroeder the seventh postwar chancellor,
exactly a month after his victory over the veteran chancellor
Helmut Kohl in the September general elections.
</P>
<P>
The new Bundestag, the lower house of parliament which was
formed on Monday, elected Schroeder by a vote of 351 to 287, with
27 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder will be officially named chancellor by Germany
President Roman Herzog later Tuesday. He will take the oath of
office in parliament an hour later.
</P>
<P>
As Germany's first Social Democrat chancellor after 16 years of
conservative rule under Kohl, Schroeder will lead a coalition
government with his Social Democratic Party (SPD) sharing power
with the much smaller ecologist Greens party to get a 21-seat
majority in parliament.
</P>
<P>
It is Germany's first center-left ruling coalition in such a
formation.
</P>
<P>
Born on April 7, 1944 in the small northern town of Mossenberg,
Schroeder was one of the five children raised by a war widow who
eked out a living as a cleaning lady. He never saw his father,
who was killed in the same year while serving in the German army
in Romania.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder graduated from Goettingen University in 1976 as a law
major. He became a state parliament member in Lower Saxony in
1980 and was elected the state premier in 1990, a post he held
until Monday.
</P>
<P>
After winning a landslide victory in the state legislature
election in March this year, Schroeder won his party's trust to be
picked as its chief candidate to challenge Kohl, who has defeated
three SPD contenders since 1982.
</P>
<P>
Describing himself as a pro-business pragmatist, Schroeder said
he understands the challenges faced up by German businesses in
coping with the global economy and pledged reforms and innovations
to improve the country's economic strength.
</P>
<P>
And remembering his miserable childhood experiences, Schroeder
also promised to concentrate on social justice at a time when
German unemployment is hovering at the near record high of over
four million.
</P>
<P>
Campaigning on a program he called a political "New Center,"
Schroeder appealed to the large pool of centrist voters, inviting
comparisons with U.S. President Bill Clinton and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
The SPD's chairman, Oskar Lafontaine, will be finance minister
in the new government.
</P>
<P>
Germany's media has been filled with speculation of a power
struggle between Schroeder and Lafontaine, which has been
repeatedly denied by both.
</P>
<P>
Also, Schroeder will have to maintain good cooperation with the
Greens, who have never held office in Bonn before.
</P>
<P>
As a party with roots in the environmental and pacifist
movements in the 1970s and 1980s, the Greens will have three
ministerial posts in Schroeder's cabinet, with party leader
Joschka Fischer as foreign minister and vice-chancellor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Securities Law Being Examined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 27 (Xinhua) -- China is taking a cautious
approach towards its young securities market as is reflected in a
draft of a securities law that emphasizes supervision and risk
prevention and avoids discussing risky derivatives.
</P>
<P>
The law, drafted six years ago, was submitted to the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress at its fifth session
that opened here this morning for deliberation.
</P>
<P>
The securities law draft covers stocks, corporate bonds, bonds
issued by government and financial institutions, mutual funds and
other securities approved by the State Council, China's highest
governing body.
</P>
<P>
It does not apply to securities futures, options and other
derivatives, which, it says, should be handled with great care.
</P>
<P>
The law drafted six years ago was examined by the top
legislature three times from 1992 to 1994 and puts emphasis on
open, fair and equal market principles and protecting investors.
</P>
<P>
It describes trading practices, transparency, adequate
information disclosure, bans insider trading, market manipulation
and other infractions. It also provides punishment for
violations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0086 </DOCNO>
