<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hyundai Boss Re-enters DPRK Through Panmunjom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Hyundai Group
founder Chung Ju-yung on Tuesday crossed the inter-Korean border
via the truce village of Panmunjom to begin his second trip to
Pyongyang with a donation of 501 head of cattle.
</P>
<P>
Chung intends to meet Kim Jong-il, the leader of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
"I hope I will meet him (DPRK leader Kim Jong-il). I plan to
discuss various issues regarding inter-Korean economic
cooperation," Chung said in the southern part of Panmunjom before
entering the northern half of the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Chung visited the DPRK in June with a donation of 500 head of
cattle, 50 trucks and food. During the visit, Hyundai reached an
agreement with the DPRK to jointly develop the tourism resources
of Mount Kumgang in the North.
</P>
<P>
Chung said that he hoped to secure a DPRK commitment on the
question of when Mount Kumgang tourism program will begin.
</P>
<P>
Originally, Hyundai planned to bring 1,000 South Koreans each
day to the mountain area starting from September 25 this year, but
failed to meet the target because of a delay in technical talks
between Hyundai and DPRK's Asia-Pacific Peace Committee.
</P>
<P>
Asked when Hyundai will start the tourism program, Chung only
said there was no problem because the Mount Kumgang tour project
had already been agreed.
</P>
<P>
"In the past four months, Hyundai has done its utmost to
realize the Mountain Kumgang tour project. In the near future,
everyone will be given the opportunity to tour Mount Kumgang
without fear," he said.
</P>
<P>
As the Mount Kumgang project is regarded as a source of hard
currency for the DPRK, observers expected it to start next month.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK is expected to earn around 100 million U.S. dollars
from the project annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
