<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Simplifying Procedures For Adoption Of Children By Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 27 (Xinhua) -- A draft of an Adoption Law
amendment that simplifies procedures for foreigners who want to
adopt Chinese children was submitted to the 5th meeting of the 9th
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee today.
</P>
<P>
An existing draft stipulates that when foreigners want to adopt
Chinese children, they must register with civil affairs
departments and get a notarization at an office approved by the
State Council.
</P>
<P>
The revised draft removes the notarization procedure. If the
parties concerned want documents notarized, they should do so in
notary offices, says Zhang Xuwu, deputy director of NPC Legal
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The former draft says that people adopting abandoned children
raised in social welfare institutions can have their own children
and may adopt more than one orphan.
</P>
<P>
Some members of the NPC Standing Committee say that the
adopting of orphans should not be limited to welfare institutions,
but some members worry that a loosening of the terms may have a
negative effect on birth control.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the NPC Legal Committee favors not revising
existing regulations and asks the civil affairs departments and
the family planning departments to cooperate in implementing the
Adoption Law.
</P>
<P>
The new draft has no age limit on people adopting grown
children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
