<HEADLINE> SAR Government Discloses Holdings of HK Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government revealed that it had spent
118 billion HK dollars (15.1 billion U.S. dollars) amassing huge
share portfolio in August this year to rout market manipulators
and defend the Hong Kong dollar's peg to the greenback.
</P>
<P>
The Exchange Fund Investment Ltd, the company created to manage
the government-acquired shares, disclosed the details of the
holdings after its first board meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman Yang Ti Liang said that the government bought shares
of all 33 blue chip companies, and now holds more than ten percent
of stakes in three firms -- Swire Pacific A, New World Development
and Cheung Kong.
</P>
<P>
The former Chief Justice and now an Executive Councilor noted
that "it would now be appropriate in the interest of the public
for the government to disclose in full the 33 Hang Seng Index
constituent stocks acquired by the Exchange Fund in its recent
market operation."
</P>
<P>
Yang said that in the future the Exchange Fund Investment
Company would disclose any incremental changes in shareholdings of
one percent or more when its stakes exceed the ten-percent
threshold, in accordance with the disclosure rules.
</P>
<P>
"This will provide a level playing field for all market
participants and its consistent with the government's wish to be
transparent and accountable," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
