<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major River Course in East China Upgraded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Sunan Canal, a major water
course in east China, passed the state assessment today after
completing a river dredge-up and expansion project.
</P>
<P>
The project, one of the key items listed by the Ministry of
Communications, started in August, 1992 and lasted for more than
five years at a cost of 2.7 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In addition to dredging, It included renovation of river
embankments, building or renovation of 42 bridges, and
afforestation. The new water way is capable to accommodate 500 dwt
vessels.
</P>
<P>
The 208-km-long canal starts from Zhenjiang City and run
through Changzhou, Wuxi, Suzhou cities and nine other cities and
provinces in east China, terminating at Yaziba which borders
Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
