<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Hosts International Heavy Crude Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The 7th International
Conference on Heavy Crude and Tar Sands was opened here today,
drawing the attendance of over 500 officials and experts from 24
countries.
</P>
<P>
The participants will conduct wide-ranging studies and
discussions around the theme of "heavy crude -- one of the
important energy sources in the 21st century" during the 4-day
meeting.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official with the organizing committee of
the conference, the world is very rich in heavy crude, with
recoverable reserves topping 400 billion tons, or 2.7 times that
of the conventional crude.
</P>
<P>
Through 20 years of development, the world's annual output of
heavy crude and tar sands has grown from 20 million tons to 100
million tons.
</P>
<P>
China has also made great headway in heavy crude development,
and has developed a series of important heavy crude production
bases, including Liaohe, Shengli, Xinjiang and Henan, with annual
heavy crude output totaling 13 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The participants will discuss subjects involving extracting
technology, processing and environmental protection at the
conference co-sponsored by the China National Petroleum Corp
(CNPC), the China National Petrochemical Corp (Sinopec) and the
Unitar Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
