<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Urges Russia to Extradite PKK Leader in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has sent a note to
Russia to extradite outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) leader
Abdullah Ocalan to Ankara, Turkish Foreign Ministry Deputy
Spokesman Sermet Atacanli said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency quoted Atacanli as
saying that Turkey asked Russia to confirm that Ocalan is in
Russia, adding that Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz had written a
letter to his Russian counterpart Yevgeny Primakov on this
issue.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli pointed out that "the Russian side has not still
confirmed that Ocalan is in Russia. Therefore, Russia has to
respond to us concerning this issue."
</P>
<P>
He said that the attitude of Turkey towards the PKK is clear,
adding that "We told the Russian side that we determined that this
man is in Russia and requested Russia to give him to us."
</P>
<P>
Turkey once massed heavy troops along the Syrian border and
issued an ultimatum, threatening to uproot the PKK bases in Syria
if Damascus continues its alleged support to the Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, Syria pledged to ban PKK on its territory and in
the Syrian-controlled Bekka Valley and agreed not to allow the PKK
militants to launch cross-border attacks on the Turkish territory.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a two-day secret meeting
held in Turkey's southern province of Adana. 
</P>
