<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Deregulates Gas Market to End Fuel Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
deregulated the liquefied petroleum gas (lpg) market in an effort
to curtail the persisting fuel crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
Special Adviser on Petroleum Resources, Aret Adams announced
the Nigerian government's decision in capital Abuja Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Post Express newspaper Tuesday quoted Adams as saying that
the new policy makes it possible for any corporate body to import
and sell the cooking gas at the Nigerian market.
</P>
<P>
For effective coordination of the deregulated market, the
official said, a lpg development committee has been set up to
develop strategies for ensuring the safety and quality of lpg
plants and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Following the scarcity of the commodity occasioned by non
production by the local refineries, the price of cooking gas has
gone up from the approved price of 250 Naira (about 2.8 U.S.
Dollars) per 12.5 kg cylinder to 1,400 Naira (about 15.5
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Nigerian government has ordered 50 shiploads of
petrol to ensure that the current fuel scarcity being experienced
nationwide will not spill into the Christmas and New Year
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Lagos State Administrator Mohammed Marwa was quoted as saying
Monday that about 100 million liters of petrol will be discharged
at the Apapa Port of Lagos within the coming week to ease the
shortage of petrol supply in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
Long queues of vehicles are still a common sight at fuel
stations in Lagos as the perennial fuel scarcity has continued in
the state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
