<HEADLINE> Philippine Government, Rebel Troops Clash in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government forces and
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels clashed again Tuesday
in Maguindanao, Southwestern Mindanao, despite a new ceasefire
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Philippine News Agency reported that the
government troops and the MILF rebels "traded a barrage of mortar
fires against each other" in Garigayan, Buldon, Maguindanao.
</P>
<P>
This was the third time the two sides clashed after they signed
their latest truce last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ricardo Torrevillas, government army spokesman, was quoted by
the agency as saying that the exchange of fires, which started at
dawn Tuesday, lasted up to 10:00 (02:00 GMT). It occurred near the
Secretary Narciso Ramos highway, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the rebel fires were directed to the headquarters of
the 39th Infantry Battalion (IB) which is stationed near
Garigayan. No one was reported hurt on the government side.
</P>
<P>
The government and the rebels forged last Saturday an agreement
ending their week-long fighting in the Datu
Piang-Shariff-Agwak-Talayan complex, also in Maguindanao.
</P>
<P>
Mortar fires, however, flew again in the same area eight hours
after the ceasefire was signed.
</P>
<P>
The warring parties once again unleashed a number of mortar
shells at each other's position in the complex Monday.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is fighting for independence of Mindanao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
