<HEADLINE>   Brazil May Support South Africa's World Cup Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The BFF's fact-finding mission follows a trip to Brazil at the
weekend by the South African 2006 World Cup bid committee's chief
executive officer Danny Jordaan. Brazil is considering bidding
for the 2006 finals.
</P>
<P>
BFF president Ricardo Texeirra will be among the visitors.
</P>
<P>
Jordaan said he is confident that he can persuade Brazilians
to shelve their plans in favor of South Africa, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The Brazilians understand how much it means to us to stage
the finals," Jordaan said.
</P>
<P>
"I was given their unconditional support in the event of
Brazil bidding for the event but falling at the first voting
hurdle when FIFA conduct the vote in 2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of International Football Association (FIFA)
starts to receive bids for 2006 World Cup next month and the
bidding ends in July 1999. A final decision will be made in March
2000.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's chances of staging the event was given a boost
Monday when FIFA president Sepp Blatter said Africa would be a
"logical" choice for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
Sports Minister Tony Banks in London, Blatter said he was looking
for an African country to fulfil the criteria for hosting the
event.
</P>
<P>
Banks said he believed England was now in a two-horse-race to
host the World Cup. "I believed it is now between us and South
Africa."
</P>
<P>
Blatter confirmed that he was expecting bids from England,
Germany, South Africa, Nigeria, morocco, Egypt and Brazil.
</P>
</TEXT>
