<HEADLINE> Cook: NATO Should Not Drop Guard on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Tuesday
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia was making serious
progress in the withdrawal of troops from Kosovo's battlefronts
but NATO should not drop its guard.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to say there is some evidence that he (Milosevic)
is now making serious progress to deliver on his commitment and
our demand that he reduce his forces, both police and army, to the
levels before the conflict," British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
told BBC radio in an interview.
</P>
<P>
But Cook didn't say whether military action against Yugoslavia
would be necessary when the NATO deadline expires at 1900 GMT on
Tuesday. He said the alliance should keep up the pressure.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether air strikes were now unlikely, Cook said, "It may
well be prudent to decide that we're not going to drop our guard,
that we're not going to end our state of readiness, that we're
going to keep it there because we know President Milosevic will
only keep up his side of the bargain if we keep the pressure on
him."
</P>
<P>
NATO ambassadors' meeting in Brussels on Tuesday afternoon
would have to decide how far Milosevic has complied with the
substantial withdrawal demanded by NATO and how far he still has
to go, Cook said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
