<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sub-Regional Organizations, ESCAP Committed to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Heads of the sub-regional
organizations in Asia and the Pacific and the Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) reiterated here
Tuesday their commitment to regional cooperation and economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
Regional cooperation and regional economic integration should
serve as a means to promote sustained development with equity and
stability in the widest possible sense, the heads noted in a joint
communique issued Tuesday after a two-day consultative meeting.
</P>
<P>
Heads of the ESCAP, the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC), the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN), the Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO) and the
(South Pacific) Forum Secretariat attended the consultative
meeting hosted by the Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the Asian Development Bank and the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP) were also present at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The heads of sub-regional organizations and ESCAP expressed
their deep satisfaction at the enhanced pace and seriousness with
which their organizations coordinated their actions to promote
cooperation in such key areas as exchange and sharing of
experiences on matters pertaining to trade liberalization,
promotion of investment, development of infrastructure, poverty
eradication, human resource development and complementing each
others' institutional capabilities in these areas to achieve
specific objectives," the joint communique said.
</P>
<P>
They pledged to continue their useful work in these areas and
strengthen cooperation among them through identifying focal points
for sharing of information and experiences, more frequent use of
each others' websites and accelerating progress toward networking
of trade-related research institutions and data bases on a
sub-regional scale.
</P>
<P>
Besides, they will seek greater cooperation in the area of
transport facilitation and infrastructure development, networking
of center of excellencies for research and training for human
resources development, dissemination of human resources
development studies as well as implementation of targeted programs
in the area of poverty eradication, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The heads stressed the continued importance attached by their
organizations to the useful role the private sectors may play in
supplementing the inter-governmental efforts in promoting
cooperation among different sub-regions in Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
"They stressed that concrete steps would be considered by their
organizations to promote such cooperation within the framework of
their agreed plans and programs as well as mandates," the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place after a financial crisis hit parts of
the world, in particular, the East Asian nations. The heads shared
their concerns on the negative consequences of the ongoing
financial crisis for the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
"They stressed that efforts are necessary to develop a
comprehensive strategy to address the root causes of this crisis
and initiate concrete measures which are in keeping with the needs
of the Asia-Pacific region and the greater interest of the global
economy at large," the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The heads urged concerned international and regional
institutions, U.N. specialized agencies and bilateral donors to
enhance and increase their assistance in keeping with the needs of
the sub-regional organizations and the ESCAP to enable them to
realize their full potentials.
</P>
<P>
In particular, they urged the UNDP to extend all possible help
and support under its regional cooperation framework, the joint
communique said.
</P>
<P>
"From this meeting, we're now moving from generalized form of
cooperation to more specific areas of cooperation," SAARC
Secretary-General Naeem U. Hasan told a press conference held
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ASEAN focuses on trade, the ECO based in
Tehran, Iran, focuses on transportation while the SAARC's priority
is poverty alleviation, so they can learn from each other.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation among sub-regional organizations in Asia and the
Pacific and the ESCAP was initiated by the ESCAP four years ago,
and the consultative meeting of the heads was held annually for
high-level consultations to strengthen cooperation among them in
the vital areas of trade, investment, development of
infrastructure, poverty eradication, human resource development
and greater people-to-people contact.
</P>
<P>
The Forum Secretariat based in Suva, Fiji, has offered to host
the next consultative meeting some time in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Takes Measures to Curb Economic Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government has
taken measures to curb economic collapse and put it back on track,
the country's media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Nine O'clock daily, the government has asked
several large loss-making enterprises to gradually close down so
that losses sustained by the economy can shrink by a minimum of 30
percent by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
A first batch will be closed down by next January 1, which will
reduce the country's loss burden by 15 percent, Economy Minister
Decebal Traian Remes was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
More enterprises will be closed at the beginning of every
quarter next year so that losses may further shrink by a minimum
of five percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts said the closure of large loss-making
enterprises may allow the Romanian economy to achieve an upward
curve.
</P>
<P>
Romania is in its second year of economic decline, after a GDP
fall of 6.6 percent in 1997. Economic predictions indicate a
decline of 4-6 percent will be in this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
