<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Population Policy Launched in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has launched its
national population policy with an aim to increase the country's
economic growth to at least six percent in real terms from 1998
onwards.
</P>
<P>
Launching the 76-page policy document in Harare Monday,
National Economic Planning Commissioner, Richard Hove, said that
the framework was aimed at influencing the population variables
and development trends in order to achieve the economic and
social goals of the nation.
</P>
<P>
"The objective of the national population policy is to raise
the quality of life for all the people," said Hove.
</P>
<P>
"This can be accomplished through appropriate development
policies and programs aimed at achieving poverty eradication,
sustained economic growth and sustainable patterns of
consumption," he added.
</P>
<P>
While the population growth rate may be declining, the
country's population is still likely to double in the next 30
years, the document says.
</P>
<P>
As a result,the nation's ability to save has been eroded as a
large proportions of the budget have to be set aside for social
services.
</P>
<P>
It is, therefore, part of the population policy that family
planning programs should continue with the the on-going efforts
to increase contraceptive availability, the document stresses.
</P>
<P>
The document quoted the 1997 population of Zimbabwe at 12
million, compared to 10.4 million in 1992, with 32 percent
residing in urban areas and 52 percent female.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's population is regarded as young with 43 percent
below the age of 15 years and only four percent aged 65 years and
above, according to the document.
</P>
<P>
Major demographic problems were beginning to manifest as a
result of the HIV/AIDS pandemic whose long term effects on
population dynamics were expected to intensify as the affected 20
percent of the adult population began to die.
</P>
<P>
The policy document has been prepared through consultations
and research activities across the country spanning over three
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's TRC Final Report to Be Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC), a special court of South Africa,
will hand over its final report to President Nelson Mandela and
make it public later this week, local press reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 3,500-page report in five volumes is expected to lay the
overwhelming blame for gross human rights violations on
successive apartheid governments and their security forces.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted unidentified TRC
sources as saying that the TRC report also accused the now ruling
African National Congress (ANC) of violating human rights during
the apartheid struggle.
</P>
<P>
However, the report acknowledged that the ANC was a liberation
movement, conducting a legitimate struggle against apartheid.
</P>
<P>
TRC, set in motion in 1995, was authorized to listen to all
those who alleged a gross violation of their human rights at the
hands of either the previous or current government, to receive
applications from those who had committed violations, in the
expectation of full amnesty for full confessions, and to provide
for appropriate reparations to the victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
