<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Arrives at Sanatorium for Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
arrived in the Barvikha sanatorium from his Gorky-9 residence on
Tuesday to undergo "a course of rehabilitation treatment."
</P>
<P>
The duration of his stay in the sanatorium near Moscow will
depend on the treatment schedule, presidential spokesman Dmitry
Yakushkin said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, suffering irregular blood pressure and "serious
fatigue" in the wake of a bout of bronchitis, cancelled a planned
Tuesday trip to Austria, heeding doctors' advice that he take a
vacation.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov left for Vienna earlier on
Tuesday in place of Yeltsin for the summit between Russia and the
European Union. Austria currently holds the rotating EU
presidency.
</P>
<P>
Before departure, Primakov called on Yeltsin at his Gorky-9
residence and the two discussed Moscow's relations with Austria
and the EU, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, 67, suffered from cold and later bronchitis earlier
this month, forcing him to cut short his visit to Kazakhstan by
one day.
</P>
<P>
He had two heart attacks in 1996 in the wake of the June 16
presidential election. He also underwent a quintuple heart bypass
surgery in November that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
