<HEADLINE> Vietnam Grants Amnesty for More 2,630 Convicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's President Tran Duc
Luong has granted amnesty for 2,630 convicts in prisons
throughout the country, Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the second special amnesty this year. The first was
made on the occasion of the National Day of Vietnam (September 2).
</P>
<P>
Under the president's latest decision, 2,630 convicts,
including 2,60 7 who were serving out their sentences, and 23
others who had not yet begun to serve their terms, have been
released.
</P>
<P>
In the first special amnesty of this year, the largest ever
since the founding of the republic in 1945, 5,219 convicts were
released.
</P>
<P>
The president's supplementary amnesty decision for 1998 has
been announced last weekend in prisons across the country.
</P>
<P>
VNA said "the special amnesty decisions for this year again
manifested the humanitarian and tolerance policy of the state of
Vietnam." 
</P>
</TEXT>
