<HEADLINE> 4 Wounded in South Lebanon's Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Four people were wounded by a
car bomb blast in Lebanon's southern biggest city of Sidon
Tuesday morning, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
At 9:05 a.m. (7:05 GMT), a huge sound was heard across the
city when the bomb in a car which was parked on Sidon's eastern
highway exploded.
</P>
<P>
A man, who is said to be a leader of the Palestinian militant
group Islamic Jihad in Sidon, his wife and and their son and
another unidentified man were moderately wounded and rushed to a
nearby hospital.
</P>
<P>
They were standing near the car when the bomb exploded, the
radio said.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, Lebanese army and interior security
forces arrived and sealed off the site and started an
investigation into the case.
</P>
<P>
Only five minutes before the bombing, a convoy of Lebanese
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri was passing by the site, the radio
said.
</P>
<P>
It has not been clear yet whether there is a link between the
bombing and the killing of two policemen in the same city last
Saturday by two motorcyclists.
</P>
<P>
Some Lebanese officials said the crime was aimed at
destabilizing the country during the presidential election in
which army commander Emile Lahoud was elected the next president
on October 15 by the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
