<HEADLINE> Primakov Leaves for Russia-EU Summit in Vienna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov left here for Vienna Tuesday on a one-day trip,
representing President Boris Yeltsin at the Russia-European Union
(EU) summit.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Primakov met Yeltsin at the president's
residence Gorki-9 outside Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who suffered irregular blood pressure and "serious
fatigue" in the wake of a bout of bronchitis, cancelled the
Tuesday trip at the last minute, heeding doctors' advice that he
take a vacation.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's entourage included Vice Premier Vladimir Bulgak,
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Minister for Economy Andrei
Shapovalyants, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Russia-EU summit, the ministers will also meet
their Austrian counterparts and discuss bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
More than 10 major economic agreements worth 600 million
U.S. dollars will be signed during the visit, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Austria currently holds the EU rotating presidency.
</P>
<P>
Observers say Russia's economic crisis is likely to be on top
of the agenda during Primakov's visit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Novye Izvestia daily said Tuesday that Primakov
was going to the Russia-EU summit in Vienna with "a begging hand."
Some reports say Moscow asked for EU food aid, although some
Russian officials denied the need for such assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
