<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Needs World Bank Loan to Tackle Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is discussing
with the World Bank for a loan to finance efforts by government
agencies to tackle the Y2K computer problem, according to
Malaysian Energy, Telecommunications and Posts Minister Leo Moggie
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The quantum of the World Bank loan sought for has not been
finalized but Malaysia hoped it would be a reasonable and
substantial, he told reporters after officiating a national
conference on the Y2K here.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia was also seeking a World Bank technical
support grant to help run the national Y2K secretariat and
seminars and courses.
</P>
<P>
In addition World Bank financial support was also sought for
the appointment of additional "verifiers" of Y2K-compliance
reports of companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government announced last week additional
allocation of 100 million ringgit (26.315 million U.S. dollars)
in the 1999 Budget to deal with the "millennium bug".
</P>
<P>
The government earlier allocated 30 million ringgit (7.894
million U.S. dollars) to defuse the computer glitch anticipated to
result in system errors or shutdowns the eve of the new millennium
when computers cannot read "00" for the year 2000 as the numerals
also represent the year 1900 in the two-digit system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
