<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
weaker Tuesday ahead of key economic data due Wednesday, which
could pave the way for the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) to ease
monetary policy following its board meeting next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After quiet session which saw trade volumes reduced to a
dribble, the local currency ended at 61.50 U.S. cents, down from
its close in local trade Monday of 61.77 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The currency traded between 61.46 U.S. cents and 61.67 U.S.
cents during the day.
</P>
<P>
"I think most market participants are sitting on the sidelines
until such times as perhaps after the RBA board meeting next
week," said Peter Whitley, foreign exchange manager for Colonial
State Bank.
</P>
<P>
"There's a distinct lack of interest in the currency at the
present time."
</P>
<P>
Whitley said the local currency had dropped nearly two U.S.
cents in the past week and "continues to drift off".
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's quarterly inflation figures, as well as wages
growth numbers scheduled for release on Thursday, are not expected
to deter RBA, Australia's central bank, from cutting interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 73.35 Japanese yen from 73.36
yen, and 1.0216 German marks from 1.0177 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
