<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Stronger on Rates Cut Hope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
closed firmer Tuesday, buoyed by the expectation that inflation
figures due out Wednesday may pave the way for the Reserve Bank to
cut interest rates. The benchmark all ordinaries index rose 19.6
points to close at 2582.9, with the all industrials index stacking
on 43.2 points to 4497.0.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index eased 1.2 points to 1046.9.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the market was up Tuesday, like Monday, on the
expectation that the September quarter Consumer Price Index (CPI)
figures out Wednesday may lead the Reserve Bank to cut rates when
it meets next week.
</P>
<P>
The banking index picked up 41.6 points to 5505.5, with
National Australia Bank rising 35 cents, or 1.72 percent, to 20.70
Australian dollars. The Commonwealth Bank of Australia firmed 13.9
cents to 19.44 Australian dollars, while the ANZ bank shed four
cents to 8.94 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Westpac bank firmed six cents to 9.54 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, diversified resources giant BHP gained
9.8 cents to 13.34 Australian dollars, global miner Rio Tinto
dropped 41 cents to 20.15 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index retreated 10.6 to 1145.8 with the spot price of
gold bullion in Sydney Tuesday afternoon traded at 292.70 U.S.
dollars an ounce, up from Monday's close of 292.60 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 324.5 million shares traded for 531.66
million U.S. dollars, with rising stocks outnumbering falling
stocks by 484 to 465 and 406 stocks steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
