ANKARA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Turkish newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Zaman (Time)
</P>
<P>
-- International Monetary Fund (IMF) Representative in Turkey,
Martin Hardy, Monday called on the Turkish government to further
advance its privatization program in order to achieve its 1998
economic targets.
</P>
<P>
"Privatization should be continued. Privatization is the way
to develop in today's world," the IMF official said.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom)
</P>
<P>
-- Turkey's National Security Council is to hold its October
meeting in which the tensions between Ankara and Damascus will be
the focus of discussion.
</P>
<P>
The government and military leaders will clarify Turkey's
stance on Syria, which allegedly supports Turkey's outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), in light of reports prepared by the
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Aksam (Evening)
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Ambassador in Moscow Nabi Sensoy Monday presented a
note to the Russian Foreign Ministry demanding the extradition of
PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan who was reportedly spotted in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Sensoy also submitted an official file on crimes committed by
Ocalan and auxiliary institutions on Russia's territory.
