<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Starts Permanent Drive to Check Air pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Dhaka, capital of Bangladesh,
started a permanent drive Tuesday to check the emission of thick
black smoke and high-pitched sound by the defective and junk
vehicles plying on the streets.
</P>
<P>
The program was inaugurated in the morning by Minister of
Forest and Environment Sayeda Sajeda Chowdhury.
</P>
<P>
The launching program was jointly organized by the Bangladesh
Road Transport Authority, the Dhaka Metropolitan Police and
magistracy and some voluntary organizations.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 250,000 defective vehicles ply in Dhaka every day,
constantly releasing thick black smoke and making high-pitched
sound which cause severe air and noise pollution, concerned
sources estimated.
</P>
<P>
Considering the fast environmental degradation, the Department
of Environment earlier also launched such drives each year and
realized penalties.
</P>
<P>
But the drive from Tuesday will be a permanent one to check the
emission of black smoke and high-pitched sound vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The government and municipal departments concerned will take
corresponding measures to control the air pollution on the basis
of the check results.
</P>
<P>
The air pollution level in Dhaka was often 5-10 times higher
than the recommended WHO (World Health Organization) guidelines
for suspended particulate matter, sulphur dioxide and airborne
lead, according to a recent WHO report.
</P>
<P>
With a population of over nine million, Dhaka has become a
capital city with the level of lead pollution in the air during
November to January being the highest in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
