<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mkapa's Anti-Corruption Drive Wins Praise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa's campaign against corruption has won praise from
the country's Attorney-General Andrew Chenge.
</P>
<P>
The president's anti-corruption drive has caused worries of
officials across the country, which is a manifestation that the
campaign has been successfully carried out, Chenge said at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper Tuesday quoted the attorney-general as
saying that his office has been approached by some big targets
complaining why they were being asked to account for their
"legally amassed" wealth.
</P>
<P>
In response, Chenge queried why "fear instead of cooperating
to account for the wealth so amassed if it was through clean
sources?"
</P>
<P>
The attorney-general said in an interview with the newspaper
that he feels so bad to learn that almost all sectors in the
society have been tainted by corruption.
</P>
<P>
He said that the war against the social vice could succeed if
everybody plays a due role.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian former vice-president and prime minister, Joseph
Warioba, has said in a report that the corruption situation in
the country is alarming.
</P>
<P>
In hospitals, for instance, bribes are demanded for the
initial registration of a patient, consultations with the doctor,
laboratory examination, provision of drugs, dressing of wounds,
admission of in-patients and general treatment, including food
service.
</P>
<P>
Since he came to office in 1995, President Mkapa has
repeatedly sounded warnings that those corrupt elements should be
thrown out of the government and pay heavily for their evil
deeds.
</P>
<P>
Several senior government officials have stepped down on
corruption scandals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
