<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Imports Climb But Growth Slowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand importers are
still buying more foreign goods than they were a year ago, but
the rate of import growth is slowing, according to Statistics New
Zealand data out Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Adjusted merchandise imports were 1.87 billion NZ dollars (967
million U.S. dollars) in September, continuing a slight downward
trend from a peak of 1.89 billion NZ dollars in May.
</P>
<P>
However, the September result is still up on the same month
last year, when goods worth adjusted 1.77 billion NZ dollars were
imported.
</P>
<P>
The data is adjusted to remove seasonal and irregular effects
which distort comparisons of the monthly data, New Zealand
Government Statistician Len Cook said.
</P>
<P>
The falling trend might be a response to a depreciation in the
NZ dollar against the currencies of New Zealand's major trading
partners, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The NZ dollar has fallen about 12.6 percent over the year to
September, pushing up the price of imports, he said.
</P>
<P>
The decline in the economic activity of New Zealand in the
first half of 1998 would also have reduced import demand, Cook
said.
</P>
<P>
Actual merchandise imports in September were 2.05 billion NZ
dollars (1.06 billion U.S. dollars), 3.2 percent higher than the
same month last year. he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
