<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Army Chief on U.N. Peace-keeping Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the Nepalese Army
Staff General Dharmapal Bar Singh Thapa said here Tuesday that the
army attaches great importance to all the activities of the United
Nations, especially the peace-keeping operations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a function held to mark the 53rd anniversary of the
founding of the United Nations and the 50th anniversary of U.N.
peace-keeping operations, Thapa said that "following the policies
of the government, the army will continue to support future U.N.
peace-keeping operations."
</P>
<P>
He said that since Nepal participated in U.N. peace-keeping
operations in 1958, some 34,000 Nepalese soldiers have been
involved and 35 Nepalese army officers and soldiers have
sacrificed their lives for the cause of peace.
</P>
<P>
He continued that as the United Nations has identified the need
for a system of "standby arrangements" with the capability of
deploying on short notice to facilitate the planning,
implementation and effectiveness of peace-keeping, Nepal has
already signed the memorandum of understanding and kept 2,000
troops on standby for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Since the Nepalese police first joined U.N. peace-keeping
mission in former Yugoslavia in March 1992, a total of 759
policemen have served in peace-keeping operations and four of them
sacrificed their lives, a senior police officer told the function.
</P>
<P>
"As a peace-loving country, Nepal wishes to see that peace,
security and progress prevail in every nook and corner of the
world," Nepali Prime Minister and Defense Minister Girija Prasad
Koirala said at the function.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, Nepal has been consistently contributing her troops
to the U.N. peace-keeping operations in many troubled parts of the
world," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, a wreath was laid at a peace memorial erected
in the U.N. complex in Nepal to remember and honor the Nepalese
who gave their lives in U.N. peace-keeping operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
