<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Meeting on 20/20 Initiative Opens in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The international meeting on the
20/20 initiative opened here Tuesday to discuss progress made on
implementation of the 20/20 initiative.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is a follow-up to the first conference held on the
20/20 initiative in Oslo, Norway in April 1996. The meeting is
hosted by the government of Vietnam and sponsored by the
governments of the Netherlands and Norway with the support of
UNICEF (United Nations Children's Fund), UNDP (United Nations
Development Program) and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from more than 70 countries and international
organizations are taking part in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The 20/20 initiative, which is the brainchild of the late Ul
Haq (UNDP) and Richard Jolly (UNICEF), provides guidelines to
mobilize resources required to achieve access to basic social
services for all, which are essential for reducing poverty.
</P>
<P>
Norway's Minister of International Development and Human Rights
Hilde F. Johnson made the opening speech at the meeting. She said
that the meeting "will have ample opportunity to discuss the
validity of the 20/20 initiative and the progress made since Oslo.
Above all, however, we should focus our attention on the future."
</P>
<P>
The meeting will close on Thursday (October 29) with adoption
of the Hanoi consensus on the 20/20 initiative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
