<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Shortens Term of Military Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 27 (Xinhua) -- An amended law which will have
a direct bearing on the interests of Chinese military personnel
was submitted to the National People's Congress (NPC), China's
highest legislative body, today.
</P>
<P>
The amended Military Service Law of the People's Republic of
China (draft) shortens the length of compulsory military service
from 3-4 years to only two years. The law also eliminates extended
military service.
</P>
<P>
Chinese land forces currently serve for three years, with
enlistment periods for naval and air force personnel set at four
years. Extended service period for army personnel range from one
to two years, with the period naval and air force personnel set at
one year.
</P>
<P>
Yu Yongbo, a member of the Central Military Commission (CMC),
explained the amended law during today's fifth meeting of
the Ninth NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
He said that excessive length of the current enlistment period
creates a great burden for many people and dampens enthusiasm for
voluntary enlistments.
</P>
<P>
"Many young people old enough to join the army hesitate because
of the long enlistment period, and the fact that parents also
object affects the number of enlistments," said Fu
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the extended service in the army will not be needed
with the establishment of the system of volunteer soldiers, Fu
added.
</P>
<P>
The draft law contains a number of stipulations on China's
system of military service and combines compulsory and volunteer
service, along with militia and reserve forces.
</P>
<P>
Volunteers currently account for 18 percent of total military
personnel, with the figure expected to reach 35 percent by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The draft also contains new stipulations on the military
service for volunteers, division of reserve forces, and subsidies
for militiamen and reserve forces during military training. Other
stipulations cover the welfare of families of compulsory soldiers,
arrangements for former servicemen and punishment for those who
have violated the related law.
</P>
<P>
Yu stressed that the amended military service law was needed to
strengthen national defense and promote military modernization.
</P>
<P>
The revisions also help to improve the quality and
effectiveness of the Chinese army and upgrade the standards of
military technology, according to Yu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
