<HEADLINE> Indonesia May Become World's Biggest Exporter of Fishery Commodities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is determined to
become the world's biggest exporter of fishery commodities as the
country has vast marine resources, which had not been exploited to
the maximum, Agriculture Minister Soleh Solahudin said.
</P>
<P>
"With the support of adequate and high-quality system,
equipment and fish species which can be further developed
intensively, Indonesia has a good chance of becoming the world's
biggest fishery commodity exporter," Solahudin said.
</P>
<P>
Inspecting the Loka Fishery Research Center at Gondol Beach in
Bali on Monday, the minister said the support facilities had
already been prepared, especially in some eastern provinces, with
the participation of big businesses and vast investment.
</P>
<P>
This project is also aimed to develop the agricultural sector
into a reliable sector, which in the past has been functioning
merely as a supporting sector, in boosting national economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's earnings from sea fishery commodity exports in 2003
had been projected to reach 2.64 billion U.S. dollars, and 7.36
billion U.S. dollars from coastal fishery commodity exports.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed optimism that the target could be
achieved as the results of intensive fishery research are now
applied by fishermen, such as in Gondol Beach.
</P>
<P>
The government is trying to devise a scheme to enable fishermen
to receive low-interest credits, such as those already enjoyed by
farmers for intensified rice and second crops cultivation, the
minister was quoted by Antara News Agency Tuesday as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
