<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Cabinet Okays New World Bank Lending Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's cabinet Monday
approved a new kind of loan program proposed by the World Bank
(WB) for future financing in the country's energy sector, media
reports here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new loan, called "Adaptable Program Lending (APL)", will be
available with the implementation of the reform programs to be
negotiated with the WB.
</P>
<P>
The loan scheme was a new type of program and it would be given
to support the energy sector reform over a particular period,
Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The reform proposals would be decided through discussions
between the WB and the Energy Ministry, he said, adding the
conditions for the reform programs to be set by the WB were
negotiable, and they were yet to be finalized.
</P>
<P>
The WB's proposals also included revision of prices of power
and gas and other infrastructural development in the sector, he
stated.
</P>
<P>
The reform program would start within two or three months, with
the WB providing a huge amount of money for the development of the
sector, he said, without mentioning the concrete sum.
</P>
<P>
The loan would support normal development schemes in the
sector, and this would be disbursed in phases after a review of
the progress of the reform package.
</P>
<P>
A large sum of money could be obtained from the WB under the
"APL", he pointed out, saying the reform program would have to be
negotiated in the first year of disbursement of loan and the
implementation of the scheme would be reviewed after a certain
period.
</P>
<P>
The WB has been pressuring the Bangladeshi government for
reform in the energy sector, including upward revision of prices
of power and gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
