<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NGOs in South Asia Plan Strategy for Climate Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Several non-government
organizations (NGOs) of South Asia are trying to forge a front
against industrialized nations on the issue of greenhouse gas
emission cuts, Business Standard said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The issue is to be thrashed out at the forthcoming global
climate convention in Buenos Aires, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Select NGOs from India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Bangladesh and
Nepal met here last week and decided that unless the principle of
equal entitlements to greenhouse gas emissions on a global level
was agreed upon, developing countries should not accept the
protocol's prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
They felt that the protocol had provisions that put developing
countries, particularly those rich in fossil fuels, at a
disadvantage and was detrimental to their economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Anil Agarwal, director, Center for Science and Environment,
said that the concept of equitable entitlement to emission rights
meant each country had the right to emit equal amounts of gases.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the entitlements should be fixed on a global per
capita basis.
</P>
<P>
The country which emitted more than its aggregate entitlement
should accordingly reduce its emission level while the country
emitting less than its aggregate entitlement should be allowed to
emit more.
</P>
<P>
Agarwal suggested that in such a case those industrialized
countries which had emitted more than their entitlement could buy
the surplus from developing countries. They could invest in
energy-efficiency measures in solar, wind and hydel sectors in the
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru, Ecuador Sign Landmark Peace Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori and his Ecuadoran counterpart Jamil Mahuad Monday signed
a landmark peace treaty ending a 57-year bloody border dispute
between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the pact is seen as highly significant for Latin
America, bringing together two rivals in an example which should
be followed throughout the region and the world.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony was held in Brasilia, capital of Brazil,
and attended by the presidents or representatives of the four
guarantor countries - Brazil, Argentina, Chile and the United
States. These countries have engaged in over a half-century
mediation.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, Peru ceded a 100-hectare hill area to
Ecuador. The area, know as Tiwintza, is of great symbolical
importance for Ecuador since its soldiers successfully defended it
against Peruvian forces during the 1995 war.
</P>
<P>
For its part, Ecuador pledged not to post any troops at
Tiwintza, eliminating the risk of another war. The territory will
be turned into an ecological reserve.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador and Peru fought three border wars over a 77-kilometer
section of their 1,600 kilometer-long border.
</P>
<P>
The last large-scale border war erupted in January 1995 and
lasted for nearly two months, resulting in 500 casualties and
causing 1.5 billion dollars of losses.
</P>
<P>
The two countries began their peace negotiations in 1995 to
re-establish a neighborly relationship based on trust and mutual
respect.
</P>
<P>
After years of slow peace talks, presidents of the two nations
met in August to work out the final details of the peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the treaty will have other benefits as both
countries will significantly decrease their military budgets.
</P>
<P>
Another gain for the two countries is a 500 million dollar loan
approved by the Interamerican Development Bank to develop their
border region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
