<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Expedite Completion of Special Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Senior-General
Than Shwe called for expediting the completion of special projects
being implemented in the country to avoid increased expenses and
hindrance of national development.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the country's Special Projects Implementation
Committee here Monday, Than Shwe, chairman of the State Peace and
Development Council, said these major projects require joint
efforts of ministries for the speedy completion instead of being
implemented by a single ministry concerned through conventional
methods.
</P>
<P>
Ministers attending the meeting disclosed that the government
has recently approved the proposed signing of contracts with
foreign companies on exploration and production of oil and gas in
Shwedaung and Padaung areas in Bago division, Rakhine and Mottama
offshore areas.
</P>
<P>
Programs of improving the waterways in four rivers of
Ayeyawaddy, Chindwin, Thanlwin and Sittoung for better transport
are being undertaken, they added.
</P>
<P>
The committee approved in 1994 numerous special projects to be
further carried out, which comprise 6 bridges, 12 dams and 11
other projects including expansion of the Thilawa Port in Yangon
and construction of Zawgyi Reservoir in Shan state.
</P>
<P>
Since late 1988, Myanmar has been implementing major projects
in the country in an effort to bring about infrastructural
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
