<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monster Storm Swirls Into Honduras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Hurricane Mitch, a
dangerous storm with winds swirling at nearly 150 mph (245 kph),
moved Monday just off Honduras' Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
People fled their coastal homes, and the Honduran government
was sending air force planes to take residents off remote
Caribbean islands in anticipation of the most powerful hurricane
in a decade to threaten Central America.
</P>
<P>
At 0000 GMT, Mitch's center was over Honduras' Swan Island and
was moving west-northwest at 8 mph (13 kph).
</P>
<P>
The monster storm is classified as category 5, the most
dangerous category of a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
President Carlos Flores sent a message to the nation on Monday,
asking residents to cooperate with authorities and take shelter.
</P>
<P>
Flores also requested officials to send medicine, food and
clothing to the coast. He also ordered helicopters to the area to
help possible victims.
</P>
<P>
Flights were also canceled at the Tegucigalpa airport Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Mitch is expected to remain in the Northwest
Caribbean for the next five days, the center said.
</P>
<P>
Forecasters say Mitch will decrease in strength over the next
72 hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
