<HEADLINE> Privatization Grows in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The Latin American sale of
state-owned companies grew by 6 percent during the July-September
period this year over the same period last year, Santiago's
Chamber of Commerce said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The downward trend registered by privatization in the first six
months of the year, with about 5 billion U.S. dollars in total
sales, ended after Brazil's telephone company sold for 18 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Latin American privatization amounted to 31 billion dollars
with the sale of Brazil's state-owned telephone company (Telebras).
</P>
<P>
Brazil ranked the first among Latin American privatization with
89.1 percent of total sales, followed by Colombia with 3.4
percent, El Salvador with 2.8 percent, and Guatemala with 1.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
Chile was not listed due to the postponement of a number of
sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
