<HEADLINE> Ivan Slavkov, I Shall Stay Head of Football Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I have examined the relevant papers. The specific status of
the BOC allows me to head the football union and the Olympic
committee at the same time. I do not see any reason why I should
leave my positions," said Slavkov.
</P>
<P>
Slavkov, son-in-law of the late communist leader Todor
Zhivkov, is a longtime BOC chairman and has been at the head of
the football union for several years.
</P>
<P>
A lot of criticism has been leveled at him lately, last year
in particular, over the current state of Bulgarian football,
which many consider poor.
</P>
<P>
Slavkov was really surprised to hear Sofia Mayor Stefan
Sofiyanski say that after its congress, the BFU will have new
leadership.
</P>
<P>
"I'll have to find out what Sofiyansky meant. I do not know
why the mayor has such ideas," the BFU and BOC chief said.
</P>
<P>
"we examined carefully the statute of the German football
union and I believe we should copy some its clauses. I will put
to the vote at the BFU congress the clauses I liked," the BFU
president added and specified he had in mind the clauses
referring to the structure of the professional and the amateur
leagues as well the organization of the congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
