<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Mandela Praises WBC for Helping Building New South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the 36th WBC annual
convention in Johannesburg, Mandela said sport in general has
been making a important contribution to the building of the new
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The WBC, which was founded in 1963 and seen as the mainstay in
boxing, expelled South Africa in 1975 because of its apartheid
policies. The body readmitted the country in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who was once an amateur boxer himself, said the
holding of the WBC convention in South Africa confirmed the
country's acceptance in the international sporting community.
</P>
<P>
He said he looked forward to the day when South Africa would
host its first WBC championship fight.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's words were seen as a call for the promoter of the
unification world heavyweight title match between Evander
Holyfield and Lennox lewis to bring the contest to the country.
</P>
<P>
WBC president Jose Sulaiman had already voiced his support for
South Africa to stage the bout between the World Boxing
Association (WBA champion and the WBC title holder.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Mandela criticized the proliferation of boxing
controlling bodies and said it was encouraging that the WBC and
the WBA, the world's oldest boxing bodies, are unifying their
rules.
</P>
<P>
"I have often wondered whether we will ever return to the days
when the term 'world champion' meant just that, and was not
dependent for its significance on what boxing controlling body
one is talking about," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also called on the WBC to be vocal in the fight
against HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
WBC president Jose Sulaiman paid tribute to Mandela for what
he had done and honored him as the champion of the world human
equality.
</P>
<P>
Sulaiman presented Mandela with an award of human dignity and
a championship belt.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
