<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Track Veterans Foster, Stones Named to Hall of Fame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Also entered the hall were distance runner Larrieu-Smith and
discus thrower Jay Silvester.
</P>
<P>
Foster, 40, won the 110-meter hurdles three times at the world
championships, took 1991 world indoor title and the silver medal
at the 1984 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
He set world records in 1986 and 1987, and ranked number one
in the world five times. He also won 10 national titles.
</P>
<P>
Stones, 44, set the world record three times and competed in
three Olympics. He was one of the world top jumpers from 1973 to
84, and won 11 national titles.
</P>
<P>
Larrieu-Smith, 45, set 35 American records in the 1,000 meters
to two miles, and won 21 national titles. She took part in five
Olympics and her career spanned four decades - from 1969 - 1992.
</P>
<P>
Silvester, 61, was a seven-time world record holder in the
discus and a member of four Olympic teams. He won a silver medal
in 1972 and a bronze medal in 1976 Games.
</P>
<P>
Hall of Fame voters included USA Track and Field officials,
members of the Track and Field Writers of America and current
Hall of Famers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
