<HEADLINE> China Gets U.N. Agriculture Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 26 (Xinhua) -- China will receive a 28 million
U.S. dollar assistance from a U.N. body to develop agriculture in
its Guizhou and Hunan provinces as part of the efforts to ease
poverty in the widespread countryside.
</P>
<P>
An agreement for this was singed here Monday by the
U.N. International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD)
President Fawzi H. Al-Sutan and the Chinese representative to IFAD.
</P>
<P>
The aid will be used to fund half of a 107-million-dollar
agriculture project in a mountainous area lying along the border
of the provinces.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government and other international organizations
will cover the remaining cost of project.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the IFAD has allocated a total of 344 million
dollars in assistance to 14 projects in China.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued Monday, the IFAD praised China for
its massive and effective nationwide anti-poverty campaign, which
has reduced the country's poor population to the present 65
million from 250 million in 10 years. 
</P>
