<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Working Transistor on Silicon Sphere Surface Fabricated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 26 (Xinhua) -- An American semiconductor
company announced Monday that it has fabricated a working
transistor on the surface of a one-millimeter silicon sphere.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time in the history of the semiconductor
industry that a transistor has been built on a spherical surface,"
said BALL Semiconductor Inc., a new Texas-based company that
researches, designs and intends to manufacture and sell spherical
silicon semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
Using a combination of traditional and unique processes, BALL
said in a news release, the researchers were able to produce a
five-micron NMOS transistor whose electrical characteristics
equaled those of a traditional wafer transistor.
</P>
<P>
NMOS, standing for N-channel MOS (metal oxide semiconductor --
one of the two categories of chip design), is a type of
microelectronic circuit used for logic and memory chips.
</P>
<P>
Required processes for fabricating the spherically-placed NMOS
transistor includes mask data generation and fabrication using the
five-micron design rule, atmospheric Chemical Vapor Deposition
(CVD), high-temperature oxidation at 1,250 degrees Celsius,
spherical resist-coating process, spherical lithography, etching
and probe-testing of the transistor, according to BALL.
</P>
<P>
The spherical lithography process allows the company to align
and expose six individual masks onto the sphere. The proven
resist-coating process requires the sphere not only drop down an
eight-meter tube through a "soap bubble" of coating material but
also dry within one second.
</P>
<P>
In July, the company announced that it succeeded in exposing
and developing a metal pattern of an integrated circuit on the
surface of a silicon sphere.
</P>
<P>
BALL said that its success proves the theory for placing a
transistor on a spherical surface. The silicon spheres could
reduce the cost of integrated circuit manufacturing by up to 90
percent through the use of hermetically sealed tubes in place of
clean rooms, and by reducing processing times to days instead of
months, the company said.
</P>
<P>
The company said that it is currently working to produce an
electrically functioning integrated circuit on the one-millimeter
sphere, inductance on the sphere and a pilot manufacturing line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
