<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Domestic Animals A Major Meat Source For Ancient Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered that the people of the Shang Dynasty (1600-1100 B.C.)
mainly ate domestic animals, which accounted for 93 percent of the
total number of animals at that time.
</P>
<P>
A group of young archaeologists at the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences reached this conclusion after researching animal
bones unearthed at Huayuanzhuang Shang Dynasty (Yinxu) ruins.
</P>
<P>
They says that domestic animals accounted for less than 80
percent of the animals some 4,000 years earlier than the Yinxu
culture.
</P>
<P>
Animal remains unearthed at Huayuanzhuang include black carp,
chicken, voles, dogs, pigs, David's deer, oxen, buffalo, and sheep.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists have also discovered that pigs accounted for a
major part of these animals.
</P>
<P>
The Yinxu site is in the city of Anyang in Henan province,
where the earliest known Chinese characters inscribed on animal
bones were unearthed. They were first discovered in 1899.
</P>
<P>
Other valuable finds there include foundations of palaces and
temples, tombs, bronzes, jade carvings, and oracle bones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
