<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Rocks Northeastern Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- A strong earthquake
with a magnitude of 5.7 on the Richter scale rocked northeastern
Colombia Monday, but there were no immediate reports of injuries
or damage, seismologists said.
</P>
<P>
The quake, which struck the Cordillera Oriental Andean mountain
area at 4:55 p.m. (2155 GMT), was centered deep under the earth's
surface about 48 kilometers southeast of Bucaramanga city,
Santander Province, the National Seismological Institute said.
</P>
<P>
The tremor, which was felt in the capital and other major
cities, was powerful enough to cause serious damage in a populated
area. A quake measuring six or more on the Richter scale can cause
severe damage.
</P>
<P>
But the institute said the shock was not expected to be
destructive since its epicenter was nearly 100 miles underground.
</P>
<P>
The mountain area bordering Venezuela is a seismic area with
more than 20 temblors taking place there daily, it said.
</P>
<P>
The quake was also felt in the western Venezuelan state of
Tachira, which borders the Colombian department of Santander.
</P>
<P>
No casualties or damages were reported so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
