<HEADLINE> Electronic Business Popular in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Electronic business is growing
in popularity in China, where 78.1 percent of the more than one
million Internet users want to shop on-line.
</P>
<P>
To meet this demand, cities like Beijing, Shanghai, Shenzhen,
and Xiamen have opened on-line homepages since the spring of 1996,
when the Xinhua Bookstore in Hangzhou, the capital of Zhejiang
province, started a website and China's first electronic business.
</P>
<P>
The address "www.hot100.com.cn:" of an on-line shopping outlet
started by the First General Merchandise Co. Ltd. of Xiamen, in
Fujian province, has proven the most successful.
</P>
<P>
Some 210,000 people have visited the website since the Xiamen
company opened it in September 1997, from Japan, Australia,
Singapore, Hong Kong and many other countries.
</P>
<P>
Che Wancheng, the company's general manager, said that
E-commerce has helped them increase sales, better understand
market trends, and has been a good publicity tool.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 factories in Xiamen have opened homepages using
the website address of Che's company.
</P>
<P>
Che predicted that by the end of this year, there will be some
100,000 people looking at his company's website address each month.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Data Corporation, 7.6 billion
U.S. dollars worth of goods were sold over the Internet globally
last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
