<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Cuts Discount Rate to 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Italy Monday cut the
discount rate to 4 percent after weeks of pressure from
politicians and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
The cut, the first since the half-point cut on April 21, will
come into effect on Tuesday, the central bank announced.
</P>
<P>
It also said its lombard, or fixed-term advance rate, would be
cut on the same day from 6.5 percent to 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank said it was cutting the rates because inflation
appeared firmly under control, demand remained week and tax
revenues were holding up despite recent reform.
</P>
<P>
The move is seen as a response to calls made by other central
banks in the future euro-zone to cut Italy's rates quickly to
converge with its partners in time for the launch of the single
currency.
</P>
<P>
Rates throughout the 11 founding members of the European Single
Currency have to reach the 3.3 percent basic rate operative in
France and Germany by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi hailed the cut,
saying the new currency would help spur economic growth and that
the euro region has proven to be a haven of stability.
</P>
<P>
"The age of euro is about to begin," Ciampi said in a
statement. "Italy is part of it. On the single currency, we will
be able to build a more secure future of growth and work." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
