<HEADLINE> Consumer Credit Now Available in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 27 (Xinhua) -- Paying by instalments may have
been a common practice for a long time in many countries, but it
was not available in China until very recently.
</P>
<P>
China's commercial banks used to restrict their loans to
industries but they are now providing individuals with credit
services, allowing more Chinese to spend future income.
</P>
<P>
One female customer in Shanghai is among the first group of
credit users and has bought 13 household items, including a color
TV, an air-conditioner, a washing machine, a refrigerator and a
fax machine by paying instalments since 1993.
</P>
<P>
It benefits both her and society buying what she needs with a
credit card, she said.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.34 million households in 340 cities have got loans
for housing from the Construction Bank of China since it started
providing them at the end of the 1980s. It provided individuals
with a total of 15.9 billion yuan in housing loans last year.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the bank began to experiment with automobile
loans in Beijing and Shanghai, and it was no more than the
announcement was made when 58 people in Shanghai asked for loans
at the local branch.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Enzhao, head of the bank's Shanghai Branch, said that
they are considering combined housing and automobile loans in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
A recent study in Shanghai found that over 68 percent of the
local people are ready to buy on credit. Another survey in five
cities in the first quarter of this year found that 58.2 percent
of the people think that consumer credit is necessary.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that consumer credit will greatly help stimulate
the home market because the country has a buyers' market after
leaving the period of commodity shortages.
</P>
<P>
"China needs a new upsurge of purchasing to help boost the
economy," said Ning Xiangdong, deputy director of the Economic
Research Center of Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
Analysts admit that there are problems with credit services
now, as elaborate procedures, a narrow range of choice, and short
payment terms prevent credit from developing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
Ding Junfa, deputy director of the State Internal Trade Bureau,
said that the government places great importance on the views of
analysts and will take steps to expand credit in the years ahead.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
