<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Contain Peso Rise to Maintain Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 27 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines, worried about export competitiveness, will not allow
the peso to rise beyond the 40 to a dollar level, the Business
Daily said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that monetary authorities are reportedly set to
implement measures aimed at preventing the peso from "appreciating
too much."
</P>
<P>
These measures include a further reduction in interest rates
and central bank moves to buy up the dollar inflows, it said.
</P>
<P>
Such measures were part of discussions held during a special
meeting of the Monetary Board of the Central Bank Monday,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary for the central bank to carry out measures
that will protect our exports from the impact of a strong peso,"
the paper quoted a well-place source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is reportedly worried that if the peso should
go beyond the 38 mark to the greenback, the Philippine exports
will become more expensive and less attractive on international
markets, the source said.
</P>
<P>
The peso soared to 41.625 to the dollar at the close Monday
from last Friday's 42.05. 
</P>
</TEXT>
