<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA -- President of the Temporary Executive Council of
Kosovo Zoran Andjelkovic said here on Monday the Albanian
terrorists in Kosovo have been defeated by now.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with European Parliament Deputy Speaker Bertal
Haardera, Andjelkovic said that ethnic Albanian terrorism in the
province had been defeated, which was a great encouragement to all
those who favored peaceful political dialogue as a means of
solving all problems, according to a statement issued by Kosovo
Information Secretariat. (Yugoslavia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Monday Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic was moving forces out of Kosovo but
it was too early to tell if he is fully complying with the
U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of movement of troops. There's some movement. We
haven't seen enough," said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
will meet on Tuesday and decide about the withdrawal. (Kosovo 1st
writethru)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Northern Ireland's First Minister David Trimble
launched a fresh initiative Monday to break the deadlock over
decommissioning which has hampered the province's peace process.
</P>
<P>
Trimble, the head of Northern Ireland's main Protestant party,
and his Catholic nationalist deputy as first minister, Seamus
Mallon, invited all parties in the province's fledgling assembly
to hold intensive consultations to try to get over the stumbling
block. (N.Ireland-Arms Deadlock)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- A new U.N. report said Monday that French
tests had found possible traces of nerve gas VX on Iraqi warhead
fragments.
</P>
<P>
The report was submitted to the United Nations Security Council
by 17 scientists from seven countries who analyzed the government
laboratories findings from the United States, France and
Switzerland on samples of Iraqi warhead fragments. (Iraq-Nerve Gas)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Tanjug, the Yugoslav news agency, on Monday
appealed to the international community to press for the release
of its two journalists kidnapped by ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The appeal came in a letter sent by Tanjug's director, Dusan
Djordjevic, to the heads of government of the Contact Group, the
rotating chairmen of the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe and the European Union. (Yugoslavia-Reporters)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- A total of 4,500 Serb troops pulled out
of Kosovo Monday in compliance with U.N. resolutions, a senior
Serb leader in Kosovo said.
</P>
<P>
Zoran Andelkovic, prime minister of the Temporary Executive
Council of Kosovo, told Xinhua that the Serbian government has now
withdrawn all of its 15,000 troops sent into Kosovo in February to
crack down the ethnic Albanian rebellion.
(Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Withdrawal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council on Monday
stressed that It would not conduct the Comprehensive review on
Iraq until Iraq resumes cooperation with the United Nations arms
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Jeremy Greenstock, President of the Security Council, made the
remarks after the Council met on Iraq this morning.
(UN-Iraq-Review) 
</P>
