<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian, Ecuadoran Presidents Hail Peace Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of Peru and
Ecuador on Monday hailed a peace agreement they signed here ending
a long-standing border dispute.
</P>
<P>
By signing the pact, Presidents Alberto Fujimori of Peru and
Jamil Mahuad of Ecuador ended the half-century dispute over a
77-kilometer section of the Andean mountains.
</P>
<P>
The agreement "laid the cement of peace," said Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
"The Amazon could have been destroyed by a war. Now we preserve
it with a peace accord," Mahuad said.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Brazil, Argentina and Chile brokered the
treaty which draws the border along the Cordillera del Condor
range, as Peru wanted.
</P>
<P>
But it granted a hill within Peruvian territory to Ecuador. The
area, known as Tiwintza, is of great symbolic importance to Quito
because its troops successfully defended it againts the Peruvian
army in the 1995 war.
</P>
<P>
Peru and Ecuador both claimed the area, which was left
undefined after a 1941 border war.
</P>
<P>
The two countries fought wars over the strip of land in 1981
and 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
