solving all problems, according to a statement issued by Kosovo
Information Secretariat,
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement reached between Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy to the Balkans Richard Holbrooke
on October 13 should be fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
Although police forces are reduced in Kosovo, the safety to all
citizens is guaranteed, said Andjelkovic.
</P>
<P>
He also said that a mission of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), including all other missions in
Kosovo, was in the interest of peace and progress, which created
elements of safety, in a belief that all of this would contribute
to normal life in the province.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Haardera expressed interest in the humanitarian
aspect of the problem and ways for distributing relief aid
intended for the threatened and displaced persons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the head of the Kosovo district, Veljko Odalovic,
also met on Monday with Haardera, the provincial information
secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
Odalovic set out that after the signing of the Agreement, the
Republic of Serbia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY)
are making huge efforts for its realization but, despite that, the
international community is pressuring our country, as confirmed by
the new U.N. Security Council Resolution which does not aim to
stabilize the situation in this region.
</P>
<P>
Odalovic stressed that all activities of the state are aimed at
the resolution of problems through peaceful means and a dialogue,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova also held talks with
Haardera on Monday over the latest development of situation in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Ruguva said there should be an irreversible withdrawal of Serb
forces from Kosovo to create climate for a political settlement of
the Kosovo crisis, according to Albanian-run Kosovo Information
Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
