<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: UK Most Attractive for Investment in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain is Europe's most
attractive location for investment, according to a new government
survey.
</P>
<P>
Britain accounts for more than a third of global investment in
the European Union and some 40 percent of the total from the
United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Within Europe itself, cross-border investment in the U.K. far
exceeds that of any other country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The findings from the government agency, Invest in Britain
Bureau, come as another report said 500,000 manufacturing jobs
will be cut in the U.K. over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The survey, based on the Treasury model of the economy,
forecast that the overall jobless total will top the 2 million
mark by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
This will mark a huge jump on the current level of 1.3 million,
the Ernst &AMP; Young-sponsored Item Club of independent forecasters
predicted.
</P>
<P>
But the report said Britain will narrowly avoid recession
despite the worldwide financial turmoil. The Item Club predicted
U.K. output growth will fall to just 0.5 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But the stock market slowdown will put the brakes on consumer
spending and inflation, leading the Bank of England to drop
interest rates from their current 7.25 percent to 6 percent by the
end of next year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Item Club said the fall in stock markets since their highs
over the summer had already had a similar effect on curbing
inflation.
</P>
<P>
While the report predicted Britain will manage to avoid a
recession, it added that the downturn will be sharp enough to
threaten Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown's spending
plans.
</P>
<P>
If the global crisis causes world stock markets to slow by a
further 20 percent over the next three months, the Treasury's
income from taxes would drop sufficiently for Brown to be forced
to review his policies.
</P>
<P>
The report comes as the Confederation of British Industry
prepares to release its quarterly report into industrial trends,
which are expected to paint a pessimistic picture of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Center for Economics and Business Research think-tank
warned of a "scaled-down version of the 1930s slump" if world
leaders fail to address the global economic problems.
</P>
<P>
The reports will all be pored over by Brown's advisers as they
go through the public accounts to produce his pre-Budget report
for 3 November.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to see growth forecasts for next year revised
down to 1 percent and will concentrate on the effect of the global
crisis on the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
