<HEADLINE> U.S. to Keep Pressure on Belgrade on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Monday Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was moving forces out
of Kosovo but it was too early to tell if he is fully complying
with the U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of movement of troops. There's some movement. We
haven't seen enough," said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
will meet on Tuesday and decide about the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said that the U.S. would
continue its pressure on Belgrade for a full compliance by
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"It is our intention to keep the pressure on because we don't
want to be in a position where the movements become show movements
and then they're returned, or the change in practices of the
police are for show or to get past a certain deadline," said
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic is under a Tuesday deadline for troop withdrawals
from Kosovo to comply with U.N. demands and avoid the threat of
NATO military action.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to decide what each particular movement has been,
but I can certainly say the trend had been and has -- had been in
the right direction; that forces did leave, we identified specific
units that did leave, that left Kosovo. That wasn't show, that
was real," Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart also said Milosevic had made some "real progress" on
Kosovo by letting in humanitarian agencies to care for the
refugees and agreeing to a timetable for autonomy negotiations
with the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
But he said the troop withdrawal remained a problem. The North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) ambassadors will meet on
Tuesday to make a final assessment about the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"The situation on the ground is that there appears to be a lot
of movement but we're going to wait until the dust settles,"
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
"But we want to make sure that that movement is real and it's
real withdrawal and not reconfiguration," said the spokesman.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
