<HEADLINE> 4,500 Serb Troops Out of Kosovo, Says Kosovo Serb Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, Yugoslavia, October 26 (Xinhua) -- A total of 4,500
Serb troops pulled out of Kosovo Monday in compliance with U.N.
resolutions, a senior Serb leader in Kosovo said.
</P>
<P>
Zoran Andelkovic, prime minister of the Temporary Executive
Council of Kosovo, told Xinhua that the Serbian government has now
withdrawn all of its 15,000 troops sent into Kosovo in February to
crack down the ethnic Albanian rebellion.
</P>
<P>
"We have pulled out of all troops and police forces to put the
number to the level of February, and the move is in our own
initiative in line with an agreement reached between President
Slobodan Milosevic and the supreme commander of NATO, Wesley
Clark" Sunday, Andelkovic said.
</P>
<P>
After 18 hours of intensive talks, Milosevic assured Clark in
Belgrade Sunday that Yugoslavia will withdraw enough of its force
from Kosovo by a Tuesday NATO deadline to avoid possible air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
NATO threatened air strikes against Yugoslavia on October 13
unless all the additional Serb forces had been withdrawn from
Kosovo by October 17. It then extended the deadline until October
27 to give Yugoslav leaders more time to reduce their forces to
the level demanded by a U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Serb-run Kosovo Media Center announced that the
Yugoslav army started the withdrawal of its troops into their
garrisons early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Three large army vehicle convoys withdrew from the regions of
Komorane, Volujak and Stimlje into their original military bases,
the center said.
</P>
<P>
Pristina police also said that all of 20 police checkpoints in
Kosovo will have been removed later Tuesday night with most of the
police units being withdrawn from Kosovo into its original bases
Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
