<HEADLINE> U.N.: French Tests Find Possible Nerve Gas on Iraqi  Warheads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 26 (Xinhua) -- A new U.N. report said
Monday that French tests had found possible traces of nerve gas VX
on Iraqi warhead fragments.
</P>
<P>
The report was submitted to the United Nations Security Council
by 17 scientists from seven countries who analyzed the government
laboratories findings from the United States, France and
Switzerland on samples of Iraqi warhead fragments.
</P>
<P>
France, according to the report, found a "degradation product"
of a nerve agent in one sample, which could be VX, or other nerve
agents called Sarin and Soman.
</P>
<P>
But the report from the experts said tests from French and
Swiss laboratories and a second round of American tests all found
chemicals associated with a decontamination compound, suggesting
that an attempt had been at some point to remove traces of any
nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. army laboratory said in June that it found traces of VX
on samples of Iraqi warhead fragments it analyzed. Iraq accused
the Untied States of faking the results and insisted that French
and Swiss laboratories test them. Samples from different areas of
a warhead dump in Iraq were then given to Swiss and French
government laboratories.
</P>
<P>
The report said tests from Switzerland proved negative as did a
second round of U.S. tests from other samples.
</P>
<P>
Its conclusions signified that Iraq probably had hidden
information on its ability to put VX into warheads and now had to
account for its past program so that U.N. inspectors could
determine if all the dangerous arms were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The experts, called together by the United Nations Special
Commission in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, met at U.N. Headquarters Thursday and Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
