<HEADLINE> UK Mnister: Europe Needs Structural Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- A senior British minister Monday
stressed the importance of structural reforms as a way to solve
the economic problems for Europe, warning against "magical fixes."
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State for Trade and Industry Peter Mandelson,
addressing a business dinner in Liverpool, said, "Of course we
must take action to promote jobs and growth. But we must do so in
a sensible way and without sacrificing the benefits that Europe
has secured from prudent finances and stable levels of low
inflation."
</P>
<P>
The minister said Britain would remain a powerful voice urging
the EU to stick to the path of economic reform.
</P>
<P>
"No one believes that we can solve our problems by propping up
companies whose time has come or that there are magical short-term
macroeconomic fixes. Our long-term prosperity depends on
governments throughout Europe recognizing that structural reforms
matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
At a weekend informal summit in Poertschach, the first since
the election of a leftwing government in Germany, EU leaders
endorsed ambitious plans to boost demand and jobs.
</P>
<P>
British media generally see it as a swing back to the kind of
Keynsian pump-priming policies which Blair's government has always
criticized.
</P>
<P>
Also, the minister said that despite Britain's absence from the
launch of the single currency next year, "no one should doubt our
policy, we support the principle and will work to ensure the
euro's success."
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the euro would have a "dramatic and
galvanizing effect" and would leave no space for "high charges and
consumer rip-offs" and a big stimulus to competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
