<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Reports Big Increase in Third-quarter Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. largest
telecommunication company, AT&AMP;T Corp. Monday reported a 68 percent
rise in its third-quarter profit due to cost-cutting and stronger
revenue from wireless service.
</P>
<P>
The profit easily beaten the expectations of Wall Street
analysts. The increased sales offset a further drop in the
company's core long-distance business, which fell by 171 million
U.S. dollars to 5.81 billion U.S. dollars amid continued strong
competition from low-cost providers.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunication giant said that it earned 1.96 billion
U.S. dollars in the three months ended September 30. That was up
from a profit of 1.16 billion U.S. dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T cut its expenses by nearly nine percent in the quarter,
including a 14.5 percent reduction in overhead costs.
</P>
<P>
Its revenue from wireless services rose by 19.4 percent while
its revenue from business services including high-data services
went up by 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T Chairman C. Michael Armstrong told analysts Monday that he
was pleased with the results of the third quarter, but added,
"There's no question in my mind or any minds of the leadership we
still have further to go."
</P>
<P>
Armstrong has been on an aggressive drive to cut costs in part
to pay for expensive new investment. He enticed some 15,000
employees to retire so far this year, 10,000 in the third quarter
alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
