<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Lauds Ecuador-Peru Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, the Security Council and the 53rd
General Assembly session issued separate statements, extending a
warm welcome to an agreement signed by Ecuador and Peru to end
their long-standing border disputes.
</P>
<P>
A statement said that the secretary-general "warmly welcomes"
the agreement and "wishes to commend the Guarantor Countries of
the 1942 Rio Protocol for their invaluable role in achieving a
solution to this dispute."
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Ecuador and Peru on Monday morning signed an
agreement in Brasilia to end their long-standing border disputes.
</P>
<P>
The president of the Security Council for the month of October,
Jeremy Greenstock of the United Kingdom, issued a statement,
saying that "Security Council warmly welcomed the global and
definitive peace agreement between Ecuador and Peru, and the the
Brasilia Final Act which was signed today in Brasilia by the
presidents of Ecuador and Peru."
</P>
<P>
"This important event... constitutes a peaceful solution to the
border dispute between Peru and Ecuador," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, the spokesman for the president of the 53rd
General Assembly session, Didier Opertti, said in a statement that
"the president of the 53rd session would like to express his
satisfaction and joy on the agreement reached today between
Ecuador and Peru, giving a global and definitive solution to
territorial differences between those two countries."
</P>
<P>
The statement said that "Apart from the great importance of
this agreement for the cause of peace, not only in the region but
also in the global context, the (General Assembly) president
congratulates the Governments of Ecuador and Peru for the spirit
of dialogue and understanding."
</P>
<P>
The three separate statements all praised the four guarantor
countries, namely Argentina, Brazil, Chile and the United States,
for their efforts to help bring about a peaceful end to the border
dispute between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
In January 1995, conflicts broke out in the border areas
between Ecuador and Peru. The two countries signed a truce pact in
March 1995, after the mediation by the four guarantor countries.
In January 1996, the foreign ministers of the two countries began
consultations on issues related to negotiations in Lima, Peru.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Irish Leaders in New Effort to Break Arms Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's First
Minister David Trimble launched a fresh initiative Monday to
break the deadlock over decommissioning which has hampered the
province's peace process.
</P>
<P>
Trimble, the head of Northern Ireland's main Protestant party,
and his Catholic nationalist deputy as first minister, Seamus
Mallon, invited all parties in the province's fledgling assembly
to hold intensive consultations to try to get over the stumbling
block.
</P>
<P>
Under the Good Friday agreement signed in April, October 31 was
penciled in as a psychologically important deadline, when Northern
Ireland's rival parties were due to have agreed on the composition
of a ministerial executive and on the scope of new bodies to forge
closer links between the British-ruled province and the Irish
Republic to the south.
</P>
<P>
But a row over the scrapping of guerrilla arms, or
"decommissioning," has delayed political progress and Mallon
acknowledged Monday that the October 31 deadline was likely to
slip.
</P>
<P>
"That is actually the price we're paying for the deadlock on
decommissioning. And it is a very high price," Reuters quoted
Mallon as telling the assembly.
</P>
<P>
"I feel a deep sense of frustration and I believe that
frustration is shared by all members of this assembly, especially
because people realize the enormous opportunity and potential that
exists at this present time," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Trimble, members of Sinn Fein cannot take their
seats on the new executive, which will administer vast swathes of
daily life in Northern Ireland, until the military wing of the
Irish Republican Army (IRA) has scrapped some of the weapons used
in the past against British rule.
</P>
<P>
But Sinn Fein says the Good Friday agreement sets no such
condition for joining the executive and Irish Prime Minister Berie
Ahern said at the weekend there was no prospect of any handover of
arms in the short term.
</P>
<P>
Northern Irish politicians and British ministers insist that
missing Saturday's deadline will not bring Northern Ireland back
to the brink of political crisis.
</P>
<P>
But they say the lesson of long efforts to bring peace to the
province is the need to maintain political momentum. As such, Mo
Mowlam, the British cabinet minister responsible for Northern
Ireland, welcomed the Trimble/Mallon initiative.
</P>
<P>
"It is vital that the Good Friday agreement keeps moving
forward on all fronts, including the identification of North-South
bodies and ministerial portfolios, as well as decommissioning,"
she said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"I hope these discussions will produce a consensus and I stand
ready, along with the prime minister and other ministers, to help
whenever and in whatever way I can," the Northern Ireland
secretary said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
