<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Food Retailers Challenge EU Price Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 26 (Xinhua) - European food retailers on Monday
challenged the need for an EU probe into differing farm gate and
retail price trends and denied they were pocketing price cuts.
</P>
<P>
British supermarkets, four of which are undergoing a local
anti-trust investigation, said they would comply with a proposed
European Union-level investigation, but denied shelf prices failed
to reflect lower farm gate prices, according to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
"It's clearly not true," Reuters quoted Asda Group Plc
spokesman Nick Agarwal as saying. "Whenever we can make savings we
pass them onto our customers."
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for Marks &AMP; Spencer said "We would disagree that
we are profiting from (lower wholesale prices). That's not the
case."
</P>
<P>
EU officials said on Friday that Farm Commissioner Franz
Fischler had ordered a study into why consumers often failed to
benefit from falling farm prices. The investigation would focus on
the growing power of multinationals and their ability to set food
prices regardless of current market conditions.
</P>
<P>
"It is quite surprising that despite often quite dramatic
decreases in the price paid to the farmer for his product, the
consumer price in the shops remains virtually stable," Fischler
wrote in a letter to Consumer Affairs Commissioner Emma Bonino.
</P>
<P>
His words underlined fears that upcoming farm reforms, which
may slash EU guaranteed prices for cereals, beef and dairy
products, in favor of direct aid to farmers, could leave
consumers out of pocket unless lower farm prices are passed on.
</P>
<P>
Britain's National Farmers Union (NFU) said it would welcome an
EU probe into an issue that has rankled in relations with
retailers since the 1960s, before the dominance of supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
"We support this type of action," NFU Policy Director Ian
Gardiner was quoted by Reuters as saying. "We need more facts out
in the open so that we can start to lance some boils and throw out
some red herrings."
</P>
<P>
He said external pressures, such as lower demand from
economically-troubled Russia and a strong pound, exacerbated a
problem that had seemed less of a worry in better times, according
to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
French industry sources defended supermarkets, saying it was
hard to pass on savings with processed products as retailers had
less control over fixed costs. Retailers could be reluctant to
adjust prices too quickly when farm prices fluctuated as this
could send wrong signals to consumers, the source added.
</P>
<P>
Supermarkets declined to go into detail on their price tags for
pork, where live hog prices have plummeted to 25 year lows, but
said that price savings were passed on across the board.
</P>
<P>
"When you get much lower prices for farm products, you pass
them on because the market dictates it. That's competition and it
works very well here in Europe," Reuters quoted Hans Gobes,
spokesman for Dutch supermarket giant Ahold as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said pork prices in Dutch supermarkets were currently "the
best bargains you have ever seen".
</P>
<P>
Tesco Plc called Fischler's letter an "interesting development"
and maintained that it passed on any cost savings while rival Asda
said a 10 percent drop in the cost of lamb in the past year had
been passed on in full to the consumer.
</P>
<P>
In a statement this month, Safeway threw down the gauntlet to
critics, detailing the cost of buying, transporting, slaughtering,
processing and packaging its lambs.
</P>
<P>
"Safeway scotches rumors that it is profiting at farmers'
expense or ripping off customers by revealing the costs it pays,"
it said. "Depending on wastage levels at stores, the company makes
little or no net profit selling fresh lamb."
</P>
<P>
German firms were unruffled by the spectre of an EU probe. A
spokesman for market leader Edeka said fierce competition between
five dominant players meant profit margins were much tighter than
elsewhere in Europe, and dictated that lower prices be passed on
to consumers, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
Stiff competition between French retailers similarly guaranteed
falling farm prices would filter through to customers, a spokesman
for France's Promodes said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
