<HEADLINE> No Breakthrough at Regional Meeting on Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Sources attending the regional
meeting on Congo (K) crisis said here Monday night that there was
no breakthrough at the meeting and that disagreements remained on
how to reach a consensus.
</P>
<P>
Sources told Xinhua on condition of anonymity that since there
were different interested parties involved in the war, it was not
easy to find a solution in a short time.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wamba Dia Wamba, President of the rebel Congolese
Coalition for Democracy, predicted that the meeting was doomed to
fail since the rebels were denied direct negotiations with other
parties.
</P>
<P>
The crisis in Congo (K) was a political one, which could only
be resolved through direct negotiations between the government
and the rebels, Wamba noted.
</P>
<P>
He complained that his delegation was invited to come to
Lusaka but was denied the access to the meeting again like those
at previous meetings.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting, which is the largest since the crisis
broke out in early August, attracted about 130 delegates
including foreign and defense ministers as well as senior
officials from at least 14 African countries.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
and the 14-member Southern African Development Community (SADC)
were also represented at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
It opened at noon Monday and was followed by a closed-door
meeting which lasted for five hours in the afternoon and early
evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's CJD Families Condemn Health Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Relatives of those who died from
the human form of "mad cow" disease (BSE) in Britain are calling
for better care for victims.
</P>
<P>
Members of 11 families have been telling the BSE inquiry how
their relatives died and why they felt let down by a health
service that knew little about the disease.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Dorothy Churchill, the mother of
a CJD victim said she thought the standard of health care seemed
"very patchy."
</P>
<P>
"I would say the vast amount (of families) have found
shortcomings in the care and understanding and that's what we have
to get right out for the future. There's going to be more
victims... but so far the system isn't working," BBC quoted the
mother as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It depends on your postcode whether you get good care for
human BSE," she said.
</P>
<P>
Mrs Churchill and her husband David set up the Human BSE
Support Group to offer advice and information to other victims'
families after the death of their 19-year-old son Stephen.
</P>
<P>
Mr Churchill said the family was kept in the dark about
Stephen's condition.
</P>
<P>
"The only clue that we received was when we saw our son's brain
biopsy operating notes and it had in the top right-hand corner
`reason for operation' and it had `CJD?'" he said, adding that
there was little information available at the time and they relied
on the media for details.
</P>
<P>
It emerged that several relatives had carried out their own
research in the quest for information.
</P>
<P>
Stephen's sister, Dr Helen Churchill, who was a dental student
when her brother fell ill, told the inquiry she had spent many
evenings in her college medical library researching neurological
disorders.
</P>
<P>
And Gerard Callaghan, whose brother Maurice died from nvCJD,
said that his family read up on neurological illnesses to find out
what was causing Maurice's rapid deterioration.
</P>
<P>
But at a news conference later he said he was satisfied with
the care his brother received. "Maybe we were lucky but it
shouldn't be a question of luck," he said.
</P>
<P>
Frances Hall, from Durham, was one of several distraught
relatives giving evidence. She talked about her son, Peter, who
died on 8 February 1996, just before his 21st birthday.
</P>
<P>
Peter, who had been a vegetarian since the age of 15, fell ill
shortly after he began a university degree. Mrs Hall said, "He
just appeared apathetic, he lost interest in his appearance,
before that he had been a bundle of energy."
</P>
<P>
At first, Peter's doctor diagnosed depression but his condition
continued to deteriorate and he was eventually taken into
hospital.
</P>
<P>
"It was obvious this was a serious condition, and that's when I
first asked about CJD," she said.
</P>
<P>
Mrs Hall added that she had stopped buying beef five years
before Peter's illness, when BSE in cattle first hit the
headlines.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry resumes Tuesday and will publish its final report
next June, according to BBC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Army Closes Base in Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- A British military base in
Belfast will be demolished because of a reduced security risk from
terrorism in the province.
</P>
<P>
Royal Ulster Constabulary Chief Constable Ronnie Flanagan
announced on Monday that Whiterock Barracks in the centre of the
strongly republican area of West Belfast is being taken out of
service as security in the area is scaled back.
</P>
<P>
BBC quoted Flanagan as saying that the closure was part of an
ongoing security review across Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"The security situation continues to be kept under close
scrutiny and further progress will depend on the operational
assessment of the terrorist threat," he said. "Our overriding
concern must be the safety of the public and the safety of police
and military personnel."
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam welcomed the closure and
said it was a symbol of the Good Friday peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
"It is further evidence of the commitment given in the Belfast
agreement to bring about a more normal security environment," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The decision has also been welcomed by the Irish Government as
a spur to the peace process. Foreign Minister David Andrews said
the closure was "an important development in normalizing the
situation in Belfast and elsewhere in Northern Ireland - in line
with the aims and objectives of the Good Friday Agreement".
</P>
<P>
The demolition of the base, known locally as Whiterock Fort, is
the next step that began with the removal of Army foot patrols
from heavily republican areas in Belfast and Londonderry.
</P>
<P>
Border security and airport checks have also been drastically
reduced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
