<HEADLINE> Nigeria Calls for Permanent Peace Mechanism in W. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister
Ignatius Olisemeka called Monday for the establishment of a
permanent mechanism for crisis management in West Africa.
</P>
<P>
Olisemeka made the call at a meeting of foreign ministers of
the 16-member Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS),
which opened in Nigerian capital Abuja Monday, the Nigerian TV
reported Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was presided by Olisemeka, will prepare an
agenda for the forthcoming 21st summit of ECOWAS leaders
scheduled for October 30-31 in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda of the summit will be the crisis in Guinea
Bissau, which broke out in June after sacked army general
Ansumane Mane rebelled against President Joao Bernardo Vieira.
</P>
<P>
The summit is also expected to witness the inaugural issue of
the West African travelers check after years of delay, to
facilitate sub-regional trading.
</P>
<P>
Commemorative stamps will also be issued during the summit to
mark the achievement of the ECOWAS intervention force ECOMOG in
Liberia and Sierra Leone. 
</P>
