<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Says Even The Poorest Deserves The Basics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) issued a strong call on Monday for
global reaffirmation of the 20/20 initiative.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, whose goal is achievement of universal and
sustainable access to good quality basic social services, will
be the subject of an international meeting to be held in Hanoi,
Vietnam, on October 27-29, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Put forward in the early 1990s, 20/20 proposes a framework
for generating the resources needed to achieve the development
goals set by world summits and global conferences, including the
1990 World Summit for Children.
</P>
<P>
The Hanoi meeting is being co-sponsored by Norway and the
Netherlands and will be hosted by Vietnam. It will bring
together government representatives from more than 20 developing
and all donor nations and official from international organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The 20/20 initiative is based on the premise that universal
access to basic social services can be achieved by all countries,
even those with relatively low levels of per capita income,"
UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy said.
</P>
<P>
"Millions of people are still deprived of their right to
basic social services," Bellamy stated. "For instance, an
estimated 40 percent of all children in developing countries,
many of them girls, fail to complete four years of primary
education, the minimum required to ensure lasting literacy."
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF chief added that the initiative's target of 20
percent is indicative, not prescriptive. "The share will vary
from country to country but, at the global level, the allocation
of about 20 percent of national budgets and 20 percent of
Official Development Assistance (ODA) is required to close the
gap between current spending and the minimum level necessary to
reach universality during the first decades of the 21st
century."
</P>
<P>
"The Hanoi meeting should make it clear that providing
universal and sustained access to basic social services is
essential to the development objectives of both developing and
donor countries," Bellamy said.
</P>
<P>
"The bottom line for the world's poorest children is that,
without renewed global commitment to the 20/20 initiative, their
chances of survival will be radically and, in all too many
cases, entirely diminished."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-26 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat to Update Saudi Leaders on Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat arrived in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia,
Monday to discuss with Saudi leaders the just-concluded
Palestinian-Israeli agreement.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian ambassador to Riyadh Mustafa Deeb told the Kuwait
News Agency that Arafat would also discuss with Saudi King Fahd
Ibn Abdul-Aziz the second phase of the Oslo agreement concerning
the establishment of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Deeb said that Arafat would seek Saudi support for the
declaration of Palestinian statehood next May.
</P>
<P>
He said Arafat would also meet Saudi Crown Prince and First
Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz and other senior
officials.
</P>
<P>
Arafat signed in Washington last Friday with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu an interim land-for-peace agreement
after nine days of talks mediated by the United States.
</P>
<P>
During a cabinet meeting earlier Monday, Saudi King Fahd
welcomed the agreement and hoped it would be a springboard for a
just and comprehensive peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had already been to Egypt, Algeria, Morocco and Tunisia
in his shuttle tour in Arab states to update their leaders on the
new Palestinian-Israeli deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Opposition Threatens to Withdraw from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho opposition
parties Monday threatened to withdraw from the Southern African
Development Community-sponsored multi-party talks, accusing South
Africa of double standards.
</P>
<P>
The talks were designed to establish a structure to bring
political stability to the strife-torn mountain kingdom during an
18-month run-up to fresh elections.
</P>
<P>
"With the new developments in Lesotho, where South Africa is
changing its strategy and combing up our country instead of
keeping peace, we are wondering whether these talks will serve
our common interest," South African Press Association (SAPA)
quoted Lesotho opposition party alliance spokesman Vincent Malebo
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Malebo complained that the multi-party talks were being used
to keep Lesotho's opposition parties quiet while South Africa
extended its occupation of the country.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also claimed that detained Lesotho soldiers,
held on suspicion of mutiny, were being tortured and maltreated,
despite denial of these allegation on Friday by the Lesotho
military authority.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho has been in political crisis since August when
opposition parties claimed the May 23 election was rigged in
favor of the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy. Social
turmoil, including looting and arson occurred in early September.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of the Lesotho government, South Africa and
Botswana imposed a military intervention in the kingdom in the
name of the SADC. By early October, the situation in the country
has stabilized, and the LCD and the opposition party alliance
started peace talks chaired by South African Safety and Security
Minister Sydney Mufamadi.
</P>
<P>
After two rounds of talks, Lesotho ruling and opposition
parties have in principle agreed to hold a fresh election within
18 months.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted an unidentified source as saying that Lesotho's
opposition alliance and the LCD had written letters to Mufamadi,
in which they had complained about problems experienced during
the talks.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi, who is leading the SADC delegation in the
multi-party talks, confirmed Monday that he had received letters
from both sides. He declined to reveal and comment on the content
of the letters.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, arrangements were being made to find a
suitable date for all parties to meet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
