<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urges Yugoslavia to Comply With UN Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 26 (Xinhua) -- European Union foreign
ministers urged on Monday that Yugoslavia comply with United
Nations resolutions and allow refugees to return home to avoid a
humanitarian catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schussel told the press
after the day's foreign minister council meeting that a 10-point
action plan was worked out concerning the return of 10,000 to
20,000 refugees still remained in the open in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers agreed on a project home plan to offer
Kosovar refugees with immediate relief by providing shelter and
care in villages or places nearby.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers also agreed on prompt despatch of
international observers to ensure security for the return of
refugees through a 24-hour presence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
decided on Sunday to immediately deploy the 2,000-member
verification mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Schussel said that the European Union member states combined to
provide more than half of the man power of the OSCE-led
verification mission.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Germany each agreed to provide 200 verifiers while
Italy agreed to provide between 150 and 200 verifiers. France,
though not finalized, planned to also provide 150 to 200
verifiers.
</P>
<P>
Austria, the country now holding the rotating presidency of the
European Union, Denmark and Greece each agreed to provide 50
verifiers, followed by Portugal with 30 and Luxembourg with 12.
</P>
<P>
The EU urged reduction of Serb security forces in Kosovo and
appealed to all conflicting parties to avoid any provocation and
attempt at intimidation against the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union announced that a total of 44 million ECU
(48.4 million U.S. dollars) will be made available by the end of
year for refugees wherever they are in the region.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian fund will come from the union and EU member
states.
</P>
<P>
The council meeting declared full support for the agreements
signed in Belgrade between Yugoslavia and OSCE and between
Yugoslavia and NATO on two separate occasions.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were regarded as an important step toward a
political solution to the Kosovo crisis, Schussel said.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers welcomed the United Nations Security
Council Resolution (UNSCR) 1203 adopted on Saturday that demanded
full and immediate compliance by all parties concerned with the
agreements, unilateral commitments and UNSCRs 1160 and 1199.
</P>
</TEXT>
