<HEADLINE> Annan on Lusaka Meeting on Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 26 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday said he "attaches the greatest importance to
the meeting of Foreign and Defense Ministers which opened on
Monday in Lusaka, Zambia, to discuss a cease-fire and a withdrawal
of foreign troops from the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
A statement, issued by his spokesman's office here, said Annan
"is heartened by the continuation of efforts by African leaders
and regional organizations to bring about a peaceful settlement of
the conflict in the DRC."
</P>
<P>
The statement said, "He wishes, in particular, to reiterate his
full support for the crucial role played by the Secretary-General
of the Organization of African Unity in the discussions leading to
the Lusaka meeting."
</P>
<P>
Annan, the statement said, urges the parties to the conflict
"to show the maturity, will and statesmanship needed to reach a
compromise for an immediate ceasefire and an early withdrawal of
troops."
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka meeting "gives them a unique opportunity to
demonstrate to the world their concern for the well-being of the
Congolese people and their commitment to the restoration of
peace," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General calls yet again on all those in a
position of authority in the DRC to put an end to incitements to
ethnic violence and to hate propaganda, and to state publicly
their condemnation of such incitements," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
On October 22, Jeremy Greenstock, president of the U.N.
Security Council, reaffirmed to the press here that "ending the
cycle of human rights violations and the culture of impunity is a
necessary element for any lasting settlement of the crisis in the
region."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary-General is represented in Lusaka by Ibrahima
Fall, U.N. assistant secretary-General for political affairs,
whose delegation includes Berhanu Dinka, Annan's representative
for the Great Lakes Region and regional humanitarian adviser, and
two military advisers.
</P>
<P>
The two military advisers are expected to advise on the
technical aspects of a ceasefire and withdrawal of troops, as they
did at the September 10-12 meeting in Addis Ababa, capital of
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts broke out in August this year after the Tutsi-led
armed factions rose up in eastern Congo (K) to topple the
government of President Laurent Kabila. Angola, Namibia and Zambia
sent troops into Congo (K) to help President Kabila fight again
rebels.
</P>
<P>
With the widening of the crisis, there are growing concerns
that more and more African countries will be drawn into the
conflict, making the regional crisis a continental one.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, under the leadership of Annan who is the
first U.N. Secretary-General from black Africa, has given much
attention and energy to end conflicts and promote peaceful
solutions in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
