<HEADLINE> German New Parliament Holds Inaugural Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Germany's new parliament held its
inaugural session on Monday with the election of an Eastern German
Social Democrat as its leader.
</P>
<P>
Wolfgang Thierse, 55, was elected as the new Bundestag
president to replace his predecessor, Rita Suessmuth, from the
outgoing chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Union
(CDU).
</P>
<P>
It marks the first time that an eastern German politician has
made it to a high national post since Germany's reunification in
1990.
</P>
<P>
In protocol terms, Thierse ranks just after German President
Roman Herzog and ahead of the incoming chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
The SPD emerged as the strongest party in the 669-seat new
parliament after winning the general elections on September 27. It
holds 298 parliamentary seats compared with 245 seats for the
combined parliamentary group of Kohl's CDU and Bavarian sister
party, Christian Social Union (CSU).
</P>
<P>
The ecologist Greens party, which will join Schroeder's
government as a junior partner, holds 47 seats, while the Free
Democratic Party (FDP), the junior partner in Kohl's government,
has 43 seats.
</P>
<P>
The Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS), which grew out of the
former East Germany's communist party, has won 36 seats in the new
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The new parliament will formally elect Schroeder chancellor on
Tuesday when he will then be sworn into office.  
</P>
</TEXT>
