<HEADLINE> U.N. Court Tough on Genocide Criminal's Hunger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Court
of Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) said Monday it will not be
intimidated or blackmailed by the hunger strike of the former
Rwandan mayor who was convicted of genocide.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Paul Akayesu, former mayor of Taba, 45, has been on
hunger strike for five days protesting against denial of his
right to the lawyer of his choice by the administration of the
United Nations court.
</P>
<P>
Akayesu was sentenced earlier this month to life imprisonment
for his role in the 1994 genocide, in which more than 500,000
people were massacred in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"The ICTR will not be persuaded or blackmailed by Mr. Akayesu
by going on a hunger strike," acting spokesman of the court
Kingsley Moghalu said in north Tanzania's Arusha town, where the
court is based.
</P>
<P>
However, Moghalu said Akayesu is free to have a lawyer of his
choice if he is prepared to finance his defense counsel.
</P>
<P>
"We have absolutely no objections in that case if Mr. Akayesu
is prepared to finance his lawyer," he said, adding that the
court has its laid-down rules and procedures to operate.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua over telephone that the court has already spent
5,000 U.S. Dollars on Akayesu's defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
He further added that the court has always respected the
rights of the accused persons "but within the framework of a U.N.
system and its established courts."
</P>
<P>
The court has given Akayesu maximum medical attention, Moghalu
said. "Of course he will not die..."
</P>
<P>
The acting spokesman, however, said he has no idea when
Akayesu will end his hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
Prison sources said Akayesu was not taking any food, but was
profusely smoking and has access to newspapers and radio.
</P>
<P>
Before his pre-sentence hearing, Akayesu dismissed his lawyers
and spoke in his own defense. Judges at the court confirmed at
the time that new lawyers would handle his appeal.
</P>
<P>
Akayesu has since indicated his desire to be represented by a
Canadian lawyer John Philpot. But the administration at the ICTR
responded that Philpot did not have the required credentials to
work at the court.
</P>
<P>
In addition, an assistant of the registry disclosed that
countries such as Canada should not be over represented among the
defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Akayesu said that the court has 41 lawyers for the accused,
and more than seven of them are Canadians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0286 </DOCNO>
