<HEADLINE> UK Trade Deficit Deteriorates In September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain's export sector
deteriorated further in September when the trade deficit with
non-EU countries widened to a record 3.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The volume of exports fell by 6.5 percent, to its lowest
monthly level since December 1996, according to the latest figures
by the Office of National Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The merchandise trade gap was much larger than expected,
compared to the 16 billion U.S. dollars in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
BBC quoted Michael Dicks of Lehman Brothers Monday as saying
that "The bad news is probably more important in the sense the
markets are looking for it."
</P>
<P>
However, as far as global figures are concerned, the UK's trade
deficit for August was better than expected at 40 billion U.S.
dollars, compared to a deficit of 64 billion U.S. dollars in July.
</P>
<P>
Economists in the City said, that was because of a fall in
imports, which may be related to the slowdown in the UK economy.
</P>
