<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Coastal
Saltworks Company Limited (COSALT) has been privatized and sold
to a British firm, M/S Purebond Limited, at 700 million Shillings
(about 1.05 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Executive Chairman of Presidential Parastatal Sector Reform
Commission (PSRC) George Mbowe said in a press statement here
Monday that an agreement for sales of all assets was signed last
Thursday by representatives of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Mbowe said the divestiture exercise covers three major factors
which include purchase at 500 million Shillings, terminal
benefits at 70 million and company liabilities 130 million.
</P>
<P>
The executive chairman said conclusion on the sale of COSALT
assets is another opportunity to revive the company which had
been virtually closed down. He said revenue from the company will
facilitate realization of the government's economic recovery
goals.
</P>
<P>
The PSRC chief said the divestiture of COSALT started in
August last year whereby a total of 10 local and foreign bidders
surfaced to compete.
</P>
<P>
Mbowe said M/S Purebond Limited will invest an estimated 2.4
billion Shillings (3.6 million U.S. Dollars) in its take-off
covering costs for modernization, rehabilitation, expansion and
diversification. 
</P>
