<HEADLINE> Pro-Kurdish Demonstrators Arrested in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- A total of 286 people who made
a pro-Kurdish demonstration in downtown Istanbul have been arrested
and are now under interrogation.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators staged a protest in the districts of Fatih
and Taksim in the largest Turkish city Sunday, smashing shops'
windows and nearby automobiles, the Anatolia News Agency said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
They clashed with riot police sent to disperse the
demonstration. No serious injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
Among the arrested was Mahmut Sakar, the Istanbul Bureau Head
of the pro-Kurdish People's Democracy Party, police said.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the demonstration cast a shadow over
the ongoing celebrations commemorating the 75th anniversary of the
founding of the Republic of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
They did not say whether the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK) was behind the incident.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting the Turkish government since 1984 in
an attempt to establish an independent Kurdish state in
southeastern Turkey. 
