<HEADLINE> Chivukuvuku Re-Elected UNITA MP Group Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Abel Chivukuvuku regained his
position as chairman of the UNITA parliament member (MP) group at
the Angolan National Assembly Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chivukuvuku won 49 of the 53 votes at the meeting for the
chairmanship of the group representing the National Union for
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), the biggest opposition
party in the country in parliament.
</P>
<P>
His main rival was Armado Pedro Jorge Caetano.
</P>
<P>
Chivukuvuku was elected as chairman of the UNITA MP group to
National Assembly for the first time on April 9, 1997. He had
resigned from the position on September 9 this year after there
appeared "UNITA Renovation Committee", a breakaway group from the
opposition party.
</P>
<P>
UNITA Renovation Committee appointed Eugenio Manuvakula, the
former secretary general of UNITA to be the new chairman of the
UNITA MP group to the National Assembly soon after its
establishment in early September.
</P>
<P>
But after the first national congress this month, many
parliament members of the UNITA Renovation Committee deemed it
"illegal" to have Manuvakula, who is not even a parliament
member, to be the MP group head. They insisted that a new
chairman be elected to take his place.
</P>
<P>
UNITA, which won 34.1 percent of the votes in the 1992
elections, has 70 seats in the 220-seat National Assembly. The 70
UNITA MPs swore in in April last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
