<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fatigued Yeltsin to Have Two-Week Vacation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 26 (Xinhua) -- President Boris Yeltsin, who was
suffering irregular blood pressure and fatigue, will start a
two-week holiday probably Wednesday, a senior aide said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin "is not ill enough to be considered disabled," Oleg
Sysuyev, first deputy chief of the presidential administration,
said in a television interview. "A two-week vacation won't do him
harm," he said.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin announced earlier
Monday that Yeltsin has canceled a planned trip to Austria and
that Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov will go to Vienna to attend
the EU-Russian summit.
</P>
<P>
Primakov is scheduled to visit Yeltsin early Tuesday before
leaving for Austria, which holds the rotating EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
Sysuyev told the Hero of the Day program on independent NTV
that Yeltsin should relax and distract himself "from the problems
he will have to deal with after he rests."
</P>
<P>
Also Monday, commenting on the cancellation of the Austria
trip, Grigory Yavlinsky, the leader of the Yabloko movement, said
Primakov is effectively acting as Russia's vice president.
</P>
<P>
"Primakov is a seasoned diplomat. It is natural that he is
going to Vienna (in place of Yeltsin)," Yavlinsky told the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Russia should not expect radical changes at the high levels of
power in the near future, Yavlinsky said.
</P>
<P>
"Everything depends on what Primakov is going to do. If he
effectively continues to perform the president's functions, the
situation will remain unchanged for a long time," Yavlinsky said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, 67, suffered from a cold and bronchitis earlier this
month, forcing him to cut short a visit to Kazakhstan by one day.
</P>
<P>
He suffered two heart attacks in 1996 in the wake of the June
16 presidential election and had quintuple heart bypass surgery in
November that year.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Yakushkin told reporters that Yeltsin had recovered
from the cold and his health was good for a man of his age.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's perceived poor health has prompted many rumors about
his ability to serve out his full term till 2000.
</P>
<P>
Brushing aside his doctors' advice, Yeltsin went ahead with
meetings at the Kremlin with senior aides several times in the
past two weeks, in an attempt to show the world that he was still
fit.
</P>
<P>
Yakushkin told reporters Monday that "recent bronchitis
combined with violations of doctors' prescriptions and overwork
resulted in the development of an asthenia condition" which
manifested itself in "unstable blood pressure and undue fatigue."
</P>
<P>
As Russian television broadcast footage of Yeltsin nearly
losing his footing at a ceremony during a recent trip to
Uzbekistan, his political opponents and other presidential
hopefuls renewed their questions on Yeltsin's fitness to serve as
head of state and supreme commander of the Russian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Even Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, formerly a staunch supporter of
Yeltsin and a strong contender for the presidency, joined the
chorus, saying Yeltsin should step down for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
Such talk was hurtful to Yeltsin, his spokesman said last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone is talking about the president's health," he said. "I
think the president feels hurt when the people he has been working
with and is still working with are discussing the subject."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin "has set very strict standards for himself," Yakushkin
said. "He has a clear goal, which is to complete his presidential
term and leave in 2000."
</P>
<P>
The president "is evidently strong and willing to fight against
any type of illness," said Yakushkin.
</P>
<P>
"That is why he keeps traveling despite objections from his
doctors," the spokesman added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
