<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-26 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interpol Endorses Egypt's Proposal on Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Criminal Police
Organization (Interpol) Monday endorsed an Egyptian proposal
calling for increased cooperation in fighting terrorism, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In the Cairo Declaration Against Terrorism adopted in its 67th
General Assembly, which opened Thursday, the Interpol affirmed
full support for Egypt's proposal on holding an international
conference under the United Nations on combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The declaration accentuated the importance of implementing
international action to strengthen police and judicial cooperation
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Obstacles should be eliminated to the extradition of fugitive
terrorists, to the sharing of information essential to criminal
investigation and to terrorism prevention measures, it said.
</P>
<P>
The declaration urged all the Interpol members to prevent their
territories from being used for the "preparation, perpetration, or
financing of acts of terrorism endangering the peace and security
of other countries."
</P>
<P>
Egypt has suffered serious terrorist attacks by Islamic
extremists, who have sought to topple its secular government and
replace it with strict Islamic rule since 1992. More than 1,200
people have been killed in the insurrection.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has accused some countries of sheltering terrorists
masterminding violence on its soil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
