<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overheated Brake Causes June Plane Crash: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Overheated brakes could have
caused a fire in a plane accident last June, killing all 11 people
on board at Mirable airport in Montreal, an official report said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Examination of the wreckage revealed extensive pre-crash fire
damage to the Propair plane's left wheel well," according to a
report from the Transportation Safety Board of Canada, which
investigated the crash.
</P>
<P>
"Overheated left brake assemblies could have provided an
ignition source for a wheel well fire," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Fairchild Metroliner plane, which was carrying nine
passengers and two crew, was flying from Dorval airport in
Montreal to Peterborough in Ontario.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after it took off from Dorval, the pilot tried to make
an emergency landing at nearby Mirabel. The plane exploded and
crashed just short of the runway.
</P>
<P>
"There have been numerous service difficulty reports of
overheated brakes on Metroliners equipped with the same brake
assemblies as those on the Propair plane," the board said.
</P>
<P>
"Seven reports made specific reference to fires or the burning
of tires or aircraft components and systems. In addition, there
have been two occurrences where overheated brakes on Metroliners
have caused major airborne fires," it noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
