<DOCNO> XIE19981027.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-26 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Survives No-Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu on Monday survived an attempt to unseat his
government after he signed a breakthrough peace deal with the
Palestinians last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset (parliament) defeated a no-confidence motion in the
government tabled by the far-right party Moledet, by a vote of
21-8.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Knesset members did not participate in the voting.
</P>
<P>
A no-confidence motion needs the support of at least 61
members of the 120-seat Knesset to topple the government.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor party, which occupies 34 seats in the
Knesset, said on Sunday that it would refrain from voting
no-confidence in the government over the next two weeks in a bid
not to hurt the implementation of the new agreement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, supported by more than 70 percent of Israelis in
a public opinion poll, will be presented to the Israeli cabinet
later this week. And the Knesset is due to vote on it at the end
of a two-day debate starting next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Labor, which favored making peace with the Palestinians, had
promised to form a "safe net" in the Knesset if Netanyahu
unblocked the Mideast peace stalemate.
</P>
<P>
But Labor will continue its effort to bring down the right-wing
Likud coalition government and expressed its support to a bill
calling for dismissing the Knesset and holding early elections
within 100 days.
</P>
<P>
The bill, also supported by some hardliners of the coalition
government, was passed on Monday in the Knesset's Law Committee.
</P>
<P>
Hanan Porat, chairman of the committee, said that the first
reading of the bill in the Knesset plenum could be held within two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli law, the early elections bill needs to be
approved in three readings before it becomes law and needs to be
backed by an absolute majority of the 120 legislators.
</P>
<P>
After nine-day marathon talks in the United States, Israel and
the Palestinians signed a peace agreement, under which Israel is
to withdraw from 13 percent of the West Bank over a 12-week
period, in return for the fulfillment of Palestinian commitment to
fight terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
