<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Asks New Leaders to Work for  Better Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Monday lauded the successful holding of September
elections in Bosnia and Herzegovina "as another important step in
the peace process," and asked the newly-elected leaders to "work
for a strengthened and united Bosnia and Herzegovina."
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the press here, the president of the
15-member Security Council, Jeremy Greenstock of the United
Kingdom, said that the council members "stressed that all
newly-elected leaders are expected to act in accordance with
constitutional principles and the Peace Agreement, and to work for
a strengthened and united Bosnia and Herzegovina."
</P>
<P>
"Members of the council underlined the need for an overall
solution of problems related to refugee returns and reiterated the
importance of full respect for the rights of refugees and
displaced persons to return to their homes in safety," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "attached particular importance to the
progress in restructuring the police throughout Bosnia and
Herzegovina, and, as part of that, to the reinforcement of a
highly effective U.N. police presence there," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The council members "urged all authorities in Bosnia and
Herzegovina and in both its Entities to make further progress in
fulfilling their obligations under the Peace Agreement, including
full cooperation with the International Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Council members will continue to follow closely the
developments in Bosnia and Herzegovina in the context of the
forthcoming ministerial meeting of the Peace Implementation
Council to be held in Madrid, capital of Spain, on December 15-16,
it added.
</P>
<P>
The council president made the statement after Carlos
Westedorp, high representative for Implementation of the Peace
Agreement on Bosnia and Herzegovina, on Monday briefed the
Security Council on the current state of the implementation
process in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also considered the latest report by the
high representative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
