<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Denies Poor States Pay More in Debt Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The World bank has denied that
Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPCs) pay more in debt service
than they receive in aid flows.
</P>
<P>
It said the ratio of gross inflows (from long-term debt and
grant) to debt service paid averaged 2:1 for the HIPCs during the
1990s and ranged upward 4:1 in half of these countries.
</P>
<P>
This was contained in a World Bank report on HIPC Initiative
which is an agreement among official creditors designed to help
the poorest, most heavily indebted countries escape from
unsustainable debt, a special story reaching here from Ghanaian
News Agency (GNA) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The HIPC initiative is also to enable poor countries to focus
their energies on building policy and institutional foundation
for sustainable development and poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
The report said annual net transfers to the HIPCs on medium
and long-term resource flows, including grants, have averaged 10
percent of GNP (Gross National Product) over the 1990-96 period.
</P>
<P>
Countries which fall under the HIPC label are those which,
among other things, are eligible for assistance only from the
World Bank's International Development Association (IDA), face an
unsustainable debt situation even after the full application of
traditional debt relief mechanisms and have established a track
record of good performance in implementing economic and social
reforms.
</P>
<P>
As at the end of last month, two years after the approval of
the initiative, decisions had been taken on debt relief for seven
countries - Bolivia, Burkina Faso, Cote d'Ivoire, Guyana, Mali,
Mozambique and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The report said the total amount of debt relief committed to
these countries amounts to more than three billion U.S. Dollars
in present value at the completion point.
</P>
<P>
In nominal terms, the amount is over six billion Dollars of
debt service relief.
</P>
<P>
It said the Debt Sustainability Analysis (DSA) for Benin and
Senegal confirmed that debt relief through existing mechanisms
was sufficient for them to attain a sustainable debt position.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary consideration is expected to be given to
Ethiopia soon while DSAs are underway for Togo and Mauritania.
That of Guinea-Bissau has been delayed because of the civil war.
</P>
<P>
The report said a number of countries, including Chad,
Guinea,Nicaragua, Niger, Tanzania and Vietnam, could possibly
reach their decision point in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
