<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Existing Home Sales Continue to Slow Down in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nationwide house
sales continued to slow down in September, the National
Association of Realtors reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, sales of existing single-family homes fell for the
second consecutive month in September, to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 4.68 million, after hitting a record 4.91 million
rate in July, according to the association.
</P>
<P>
American consumers' confidence in the economy fell in September
for the third consecutive month, according to the Conference
Board, a New York-based private research group.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believed though mortgage rates remain affordable,
below 7 percent, the increased volatility in rates in recent weeks
has put some would-be buyers off.
</P>
<P>
During one week earlier this month, First Union's rate on a
30-year, fixed-rate loan with no points jumped from 6.625 percent
on Monday to 7.25 percent on Friday, adding roughly 100 dollars to
a monthly payment on a 150,000 dollar mortgage.
</P>
<P>
The rate's since slipped back to 6.75 percent but borrowers
remain wary.
</P>
<P>
New home sales, after selling at a record seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 922,000 in June, fell in both July and August.
Construction starts of new homes and apartments, meanwhile,
declined in both August and September.
</P>
<P>
Some economists believed that even with the drop-off, this year
will be an unbelievable record year, while 1999 is forecast as a
very good year for sales, but it will not be as good as 1998.
</P>
<P>
And housing construction won't serve as one of the economy's
stellar engines of growth, as it has this year, according to a
panel of 36 forecasters assembled by the National Association for
Business Economics.
</P>
<P>
Residential construction soared at a 15 percent annual rate
during the first half of this year, accounting for one in every
six dollars added to the nation's gross domestic product. But
housing construction next year, according to the forecasters, will
advance at a lackluster 1.5 percent annual rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
