<HEADLINE> U.S. Reports Serb Troop Movements in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Monday Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was moving forces out
of Kosovo but it was too early to tell if he was fully complying
with the U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of movement of troops. There's some movement. We
haven't seen enough," said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said Milosevic had made some "real progress" on Kosovo
by letting in humanitarian agencies to care for the refugees and
agreeing to a timetable for autonomy negotiations with the
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
But he said the troop withdrawal remained a problem. The North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) ambassadors will meet Tuesday
to make a final assessment about the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"The situation on the ground is that there appears to be a lot
of movement but we're going to wait until the dust settles,"
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
"But we want to make sure that that movement is real and it's
real withdrawal and not reconfiguration," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic is under a Tuesday deadline for troop withdrawals
from Kosovo to comply with U.N. demands and avoid the threat of
NATO military action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
