<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PC Sells Well in U.S. and Worldwide in 3rd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 26 (Xinhua) -- Strong growth was
registered in the U.S. and Western European PC markets in the
third quarter despite weakness in global economies, according to a
report released Monday by an American market analysis firm.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide, PC shipments rose 15 percent over the quarter a year
ago and 13 percent sequentially, said International Data
Corporation (IDC). A total of 22.6 million PCs were shipped during
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
Total U.S. PC vendor shipments, which exclude sales by original
equipment manufacturers, grew 14 percent over the last year, with
9.52 million units. Western Europe also reported strong growth
based on a growing low cost PC market and a strong economy. But
economic woes in Russian and the Southeast Asian markets countered
the strong Western European growth. A positive growth rate in the
Japanese market showed signs of a revival in consumer demand, said
IDC.
</P>
<P>
Among the U.S. computer makers, Compaq retained its number one
position, with 1.5 million shipments and a market share of 15.8
percent. Dell, number two, maintained its high-flying growth with
1.34 million units shipped in the U.S., up 65 percent from a year
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
