<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Presses FIFA Chief on 2006 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 26 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair met world soccer governing body FIFA President Sepp Blatter
on Monday to push England's 2006 World Cup bid.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting at Downing Street Blair and Sports Minister Tony
Banks told Blatter, who took the post last June at the eve of the
World Cup finals in France, that England had the facilities,
communications and experience to host the game's biggest event.
</P>
<P>
Banks said the hour-long meeting had gone "extraordinarily
well".
</P>
<P>
Blatter said at a press conference after the meeting that he
expected England to present a strong and professional bid to host
the 2006 finals.
</P>
<P>
But he also insisted that South Africa would be the logical
choice after tournaments in the USA in 1994, in Europe in 1998 and
the forthcoming Asian World Cup in 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
